"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751383","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>NHS England has advised that the building of the new Health and Wellbeing Medical Centre is supported in principle for funding through the Estates and Technology Transformation Fund, subject to due diligence checks, including a value for money exercise.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is working closely with Birmingham Cross City Clinical Commissioning Group and remains fully committed to keeping this scheme on track, subject to satisfactory completion of checks. To support the progress of the scheme, NHS England has provided funding to assist the development of the Outline Business Case for the project.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-17T16:46:14.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751383/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751383/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Health Centres: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Health and Wellbeing Centre in College Green, Birmingham, which has been approved for investment from the NHS Estates Technology and Transformation Fund is completed on schedule.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","4557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751384","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>A key commercial feature of the sale transaction is that NHS Professionals Ltd (NHSP) must act to maintain a business model based on supplying high quality healthcare staff at low margins to National Health Service clients. Breach of this principal gives the Department the right to repurchase its shares.</p><p>As part of the competitive bidding process, bidders were required to submit business plans indicating how growing NHSP will help reduce NHS spend through a combination of greater use of ‘bank’ over agency staff, growth of products such as locum doctors and international recruitment, growth in market share, and reduced costs to customers.</p><p>The Department is currently in confidential commercial negotiations with interested bidders and cannot comment further on the nature or identity of bids. The Department will disclose the full cost of the process upon its completion.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","4597","2017-07-17T16:49:27.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751384/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751384/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","NHS Professionals: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 5 July 2017 to Question 1506, on NHS Professionals: privatisation, what estimate he has made of the annual saving to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751385","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>A key commercial feature of the sale transaction is that NHS Professionals Ltd (NHSP) must act to maintain a business model based on supplying high quality healthcare staff at low margins to National Health Service clients. Breach of this principal gives the Department the right to repurchase its shares.</p><p>As part of the competitive bidding process, bidders were required to submit business plans indicating how growing NHSP will help reduce NHS spend through a combination of greater use of ‘bank’ over agency staff, growth of products such as locum doctors and international recruitment, growth in market share, and reduced costs to customers.</p><p>The Department is currently in confidential commercial negotiations with interested bidders and cannot comment further on the nature or identity of bids. The Department will disclose the full cost of the process upon its completion.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","4596","2017-07-17T16:49:27.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751385/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751385/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","NHS Professionals: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 5 July 2017 to Question 1506, on NHS Professionals: privatisation, what the cost has been of the procurement process to date.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751386","Department of Health","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Scottish maternity and neonatal review is a well-conceived document that will be used in the deliberations of the Neonatal Review.</p><p> </p><p>Networks have been formally established in England for 15 years and are now configured as Operational Delivery Networks which provide an important role in coordinating and quality assurance of locally delivered care.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS England Clinical Reference Group is coordinating both the Neonatal Transformation Review and the progress of the Quality Surveillance Team’s Peer Review of Neonatal Services. The results of both have been designed to complement each other and minimise the work required of the local neonatal teams. Both processes will feed into the work of the Local Maternity Systems and Operational Delivery Networks over the next 12 months to ensure that we have a coordinated approach to improving the specialist care available for babies, alongside the initiatives developed by Better Births.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","4579","2017-07-20T15:28:21.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751386/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751386/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Baby Care Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms are in place to ensure co-ordination of the work of the Neonatal Transformation Review and the proposed quality surveillance programme on neonatal care.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","4578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751387","Department of Health","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Scottish maternity and neonatal review is a well-conceived document that will be used in the deliberations of the Neonatal Review.</p><p> </p><p>Networks have been formally established in England for 15 years and are now configured as Operational Delivery Networks which provide an important role in coordinating and quality assurance of locally delivered care.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS England Clinical Reference Group is coordinating both the Neonatal Transformation Review and the progress of the Quality Surveillance Team’s Peer Review of Neonatal Services. The results of both have been designed to complement each other and minimise the work required of the local neonatal teams. Both processes will feed into the work of the Local Maternity Systems and Operational Delivery Networks over the next 12 months to ensure that we have a coordinated approach to improving the specialist care available for babies, alongside the initiatives developed by Better Births.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","4578","2017-07-20T15:28:21.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751387/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751387/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Maternity Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what account will be taken of Scottish maternity and neonatal review during the neonatal transformation review process.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","4579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751388","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>In June 2016 there were 58,698 EU27 workers employed in National Health Service trusts and clinical commissioning groups. In March 2017 this had increased by 3,236 to 61,934.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is committed to ensuring that the NHS and social care system have the nurses, midwives, doctors, carers and other health professionals that it needs.</p><p> </p><p>As negotiations continue around the United Kingdom’s exit from the European Union, the Department and its arm’s length bodies will continue to support the health and care system to ensure they are able to deliver the services on which patients rely.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to monitor and analyse overall staffing levels across the NHS, and is working across Government to ensure there will continue to be sufficient staff to deliver the high quality service that patients expect.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-19T13:38:48.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751388/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751388/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Health Professions: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the reasons why healthcare professionals who are nationals of other EU member states have left the employment of the NHS since 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751389","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>NHS Digital publishes workforce statistics and the following table shows the number of qualified nurses and health visitors who are 70 and over working in the National Health Service in England at 30 September 2012 to 2016. Data for March 2017 is also provided as this is the latest available.</p><p> </p><p>The data is headcount because equality data relates to individuals.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS): Qualified nurses and health visitors by 5 year age band in NHS trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England as at 30 September each specified year and latest data as at 31 March 2017</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Qualified nurses and health visitors age profile (headcount)</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>March 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><em> </em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>70 and over</p></td><td><p>166</p></td><td><p>209</p></td><td><p>251</p></td><td><p>296</p></td><td><p>350</p></td><td><p>411</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: NHS Digital, Provisional NHS HCHS monthly workforce statistics.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-19T13:42:53.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751389/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751389/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many nurses working in the NHS in England were aged 70 years or older in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751390","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>Nationality data is not held centrally by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital publishes National Health Service workforce statistics. The latest nationality data for staff working in trusts and clinical commissioning groups, as at 31 March 2017, is available at:</p><p><a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB24214/hchs-trst-ccg-org-job-type-mar-2017.xlsx" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB24214/hchs-trst-ccg-org-job-type-mar-2017.xlsx</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-19T13:47:34.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751390/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751390/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Health Professions: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of (a) nurses, (b) junior doctors, (c) consultants, (d) midwives, (e) GPs and (f) allied health professionals are citizens of EU member states other than the UK.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751391","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>No decision has been made to close the Congenital Heart Disease service at the Royal Brompton &amp; Harefield NHS Foundation Trust.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-17T16:43:53.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751391/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751391/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Royal Brompton Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the potential number of qualified medical staff who might leave the NHS as a result of the proposed closure of congenital heart disease services at the Royal Brompton Hospital.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","4574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751392","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Department announced its intention to sell a majority shareholding in NHS Professionals Ltd in November last year (2016). The Department received a number of expressions of interests following a successful Open Day and a number of responses to pre-qualification documents. The Department is currently in confidential commercial negotiations with interested bidders and cannot comment further on the nature or identity of bids. The Department will disclose the full cost of the process upon its completion.</p><p>In 2014 a stakeholder engagement process was undertaken by the Department and NHS P about the future of NHS P which involved talking to National Health Service trusts and various stakeholders in the Department, NHS Employers and NHS Improvement.</p><p>NHS Professionals’ NHS clients, staff, representative unions, and registered workers have been kept advised of the potential sale process since its commencement in July 2016. Prior to the announcement in November 2016 on the intention to sell, an email was shared with all NHS Professionals staff explaining the nature of the process. This information was also shared with trades unions representing staff, with whom, prior meetings had also been held.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","4510 ; 4513 ; 4514","2017-07-17T16:45:32.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751392/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751392/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","NHS Professionals: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the names of the bidders competing for the contracts to run NHS Professionals.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","4516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751393","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>NHS England is in close contact with the local practices who are registering patients from Marske Medical Practice and have been asked to identify if there are any concerns or issues with capacity since the closure of Marske Medical Centre. The majority of practices are reporting no impact on appointment availability. In some cases, practices have taken on additional clinical staff to manage the increased workload.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-17T13:01:29.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751393/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751393/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Marske Medical Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of the closure of Marske Medical Centre on waiting times for primary medical care services at neighbouring practices.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","4519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751394","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>In 2015/16 there were an estimated 339,000 hospital admissions in England where alcohol was the main reason for admission. Numbers and rates have been largely unchanged since 2009/10. This data is published annually in the Public Health Outcomes Framework which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.phoutcomes.info" target="_blank">http://www.phoutcomes.info</a></p><p>The Local Alcohol Profiles for England are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/local-alcohol-profiles" target="_blank">https://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/local-alcohol-profiles</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-17T13:36:49.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751394/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751394/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of alcohol-related admissions into hospital; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","4710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751395","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>Expenditure on respiratory disease research by the Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) has increased by over two thirds from £15.7 million in 2009/10 to £26.7 million in 2015/16 (the latest available figure).</p><p> </p><p>The NIHR welcomes funding applications for research into any aspect of human health, including lung disease. These applications are subject to peer review and judged in open competition, with awards being made on the basis of the importance of the topic to patients and health and care services, value for money and scientific quality. In all disease areas, the amount of NIHR funding depends on the volume and quality of scientific activity.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-17T15:51:02.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751395/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751395/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-12","Lung Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of funding for research into lung disease; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","4711"
