"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751397","Home Office","false","2017-08-03","<p>The statement of accounts for the Home Office is published on the .GOV.UK website. The annual accounts provide a financial and narrative summary of the activities of the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>A link to the most recent available data is provided here;</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ho-annual-reports-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ho-annual-reports-and-accounts</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","4553","2017-08-03T14:06:27.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751397/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751397/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much revenue was accrued to the public purse from the premium visa service in (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","4550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751398","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>UKVI does not make routine assessments of the availability of translators and support services for visa application interviews. However each of our decision making centres maintains a register of available interpreters that they are able to utilise should an interview be required.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-17T16:17:32.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751398/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751398/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the availability of translators and other support services for visa application interviews.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","4582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751399","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-17","<p>We take the protection of individuals' personal data both online and offline, seriously. The Information Commissioner is the UK's independent authority responsible for administering and enforcing information rights and provides guidance and advice to individuals and organisations on, among other things, the protection of personal data online. The ICO has produced guidance on online safety on its website available at: <a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-the-public/online/social-networking/" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/for-the-public/online/social-networking/</a></p><p> </p><p>As part of the new computing curriculum introduced in 2014 pupils are taught how to use technology safely and respectfully, how to keep personal information private, recognise inappropriate content and behaviour, and where to go for help if they have any concerns about online content or contact.</p><p>The Government's National Cyber Security Strategy (2016-2021, https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-cyber-security-strategy-2016-to-2021), backed with £1.9 billion investment, funds the Cyber Aware campaign. Cyber Aware is a cross-government awareness and behaviour change campaign which works with a range of public and private sector partners to encourage the public (and Small and Medium Enterprises) to adopt more secure online behaviour like using a strong separate password for your email account and downloading the latest software updates.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-17T16:57:54.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751399/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751399/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Personal Records: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to educate the public of the potential dangers of posting personal information online.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751400","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Progress on resettlement under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme is indicated in quarterly immigration statistics, and is broken down by each local authority. The last set of statistics, published on 25 May, showed that 11 people have been resettled to Hackney since the scheme began. A total of 7,307 Syrians have been resettled across 235 different local authorities.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-17T15:23:34.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751400/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751400/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Syrian families have been resettled in Hackney through the Syrian Resettlement Programme.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","4556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751401","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The NCA publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number, gender, sectors and country of origin of potential victims of modern slavery in the UK. These are available on the NCA website, via the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/national-referral-mechanism-statistics" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/national-referral-mechanism-statistics</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-17T15:16:22.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751401/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751401/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will place in the Library a copy of the assessments made by the National Crime Agency which set out the number, gender, sectors and countries of origin of potential victims of modern slavery in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751402","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The National Referral Mechanism pilot has been testing a new model for identifying and referring victims, processing cases and making effective decisions.</p><p> </p><p>Interim guidance for frontline staff has been published and we will consult with stakeholders on the statutory guidance required under section 49 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 prior to publication.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-20T12:03:10.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751402/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751402/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish (a) the report of the evaluation of National Referral Mechanism pilots and (b) statutory guidance on victim identification and assistance under section 49 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","4469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751403","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Government’s policy paper (Cm 9464) is clear that the Home Office will provide a period of blanket residence permission, to start immediately on the UK’s exit from the EU for EU citizens, and their family members, lawfully resident in the UK before the date agreed with the EU.</p><p> </p><p>This will be a generic “umbrella” of temporary leave to give individuals time between the moment that free movement ends and the time that they obtain their residence document; allowing them to remain lawfully in the UK, and continue to undertake lawful activities during that interim period. Such leave, known as ‘deemed leave’ in UK law under the Immigration Act 1971, will not require an application.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-20T11:56:25.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751403/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751403/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 3708, on Immigration: EU nationals, how her Department will determine who is eligible for deemed leave.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751404","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Decisions on how the police enforce the law and deploy their available resources are the responsibility of individual Chief Officers, taking into account the specific local problems and demands with which they are faced.</p><p>The Home Office has not made any assessments into the effectiveness of the Central Motorway Police Group’s (CMPG) collaboration with the European Traffic Police Network or in maintaining network resilience and traffic flow or of the ability of West Mercia Police to provide 24 hour patrols.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","4657 ; 4659","2017-07-17T16:42:19.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751404/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751404/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Central Motorway Police Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Central Motorway Police Group's collaboration with the European Traffic Police Network on improving road safety.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","4660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751405","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Inquiry is a statutory inquiry established under the Inquiries Act. It is independent of Government. The Inquiry’s Terms of Reference have not yet been determined. The Prime Minister has asked the Inquiry team to conduct a public consultation on the Terms of Reference and make recommendations on what they should cover. Details of the consultation process are published on the Inquiry’s website (<a href="http://www.grenfelltowerinquiry.org.uk" target="_blank">www.grenfelltowerinquiry.org.uk</a>).</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-17T16:28:23.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751405/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751405/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-12","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government has issued any guidance or advice to Sir Martin Moore-Bick or set any limitations or requirements on the terms of reference for the Grenfell Tower inquiry.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","4662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751406","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Immigration Rules for the admission to the UK of adult dependent relatives were upheld as lawful by the Court of Appeal on 24 May 2017 in Britcits v The Secretary of State for the Home Department [2017] EWCA Civ 368. We will update the relevant guidance as appropriate in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-17T15:21:22.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751406/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751406/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications for the guidance given to Entry Clearance Officers of the recent Court of Appeal judgment relating to the admission to the UK of adult dependent relatives.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","4646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751407","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Decisions on how the police enforce the law and deploy their available resources are the responsibility of individual Chief Officers, taking into account the specific local problems and demands with which they are faced.</p><p>The Home Office has not made any assessments into the effectiveness of the Central Motorway Police Group’s (CMPG) collaboration with the European Traffic Police Network or in maintaining network resilience and traffic flow or of the ability of West Mercia Police to provide 24 hour patrols.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","4657 ; 4660","2017-07-17T16:42:19.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751407/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751407/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Central Motorway Police Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Central Motorway Police Group in maintaining network resilience and traffic flow.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","4659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751408","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Decisions on how the police enforce the law and deploy their available resources are the responsibility of individual Chief Officers, taking into account the specific local problems and demands with which they are faced.</p><p>The Home Office has not made any assessments into the effectiveness of the Central Motorway Police Group’s (CMPG) collaboration with the European Traffic Police Network or in maintaining network resilience and traffic flow or of the ability of West Mercia Police to provide 24 hour patrols.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","4659 ; 4660","2017-07-17T16:42:19.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751408/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751408/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Central Motorway Police Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the ability of West Mercia Police to provide 24 hour patrols following its withdrawal from the Central Motorway Police Group.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","4657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751409","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government laid a Written Ministerial Statement in both Houses on Wednesday 12 July, which conveyed the main findings of the Government’s review into the funding for Islamist extremist activity in the UK. The review was originally committed to by the former Prime Minister, David Cameron, in November 2015. The review produced a classified report.</p><p> </p><p>The Written Ministerial Statement conveys the mains findings of the review and the Government’s response. The single most important finding was that the most significant source of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK is small, private donations from UK-based individuals. Often these individuals do not appreciate the extremist credentials of those they are donating to. The Government’s response prioritises tackling the domestic sources of extremism but the Government is committed to tackling all sources, including from overseas. The Government will continue to work with its international partners to combat extremism and where necessary will raise issues of concern in our bilateral relationships. The Counter-Extremism Strategy sets out the Government’s plans for engaging internationally on extremism. The Charity Commission will be introducing a requirement on charities to declare overseas sources of funding to increase transparency in this area.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-17T16:15:40.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751409/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751409/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Radicalism: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to prevent funding reaching the UK which has originated in countries which have been identified as having funded extremism.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","4737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751410","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information in a format that can be published.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-17T15:38:48.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751410/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751410/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Immigration Controls: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the number of illegal immigrants who have entered the UK through ports in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","4745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751411","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Border Force has an established second line assurance function in the Operational Assurance Directorate (OAD). OAD has implemented a nationwide system of frontline assurance including a dedicated port inspection capability which tests compliance with operational policy, guidance and legislation and identifies cross Border Force risks and vulnerabilities.</p><p>Border Force is also regularly inspected on a systematic basis by external review bodies. Reports are published online by the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration, Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Prisons, The Independent Management Board, The Public Accounts Committee and the National Audit Office.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-17T16:47:39.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751411/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751411/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Immigration Controls: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of border control enforcement at ports across the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","4746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751412","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government laid a Written Ministerial Statement in both Houses on Wednesday 12 July, which conveyed the main findings of the Government’s review into the funding for Islamist extremist activity in the UK. The statement confirms that the Government will continue to raise issues of concern through our bilateral relationships where there is evidence of support for extremism in the UK. The Charity Commission will also be introducing a requirement on charities to declare overseas sources of funding to increase transparency in this area.</p><p>The Government’s Counter-Extremism Strategy sets out its commitment to tackling extremism in all its forms, including engaging internationally to support our efforts to defeat extremism in the UK. This includes countering the flow of extremism to the UK, whether money, people or ideology; building international partnerships with all those opposed to extremism; and disrupting extremists from entering the UK. The Government engages with a wide range of international partners on these issues and supports implementation of the UN Plan of Action to Prevent Violent Extremism and the UN Global CT Strategy. We will continue to work closely with our partners to give further momentum to the UN’s efforts.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-17T16:00:14.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751412/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751412/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Written Statement, HCWS39, published on 12 July 2017, on extremism, to the governments of which countries she (a) has made and (b) plans to make representations on countering extremism and violent extremism.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","4736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751413","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Digital Economy Act requires the Secretary of State, before issuing a code of practice, to consult social media providers to whom the code is intended to give guidance and such other persons as the Secretary of State considers it appropriate to consult. We will take forward this consultation as part of the Internet Safety Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of what the code of practice will include will be decided following this consultation.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","4727 ; 4728 ; 4729","2017-07-19T13:21:04.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751413/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751413/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what mechanisms she plans to put in place to revise the code of practice for providers of online social media platforms to respond to future technical developments.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751414","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Digital Economy Act requires the Secretary of State, before issuing a code of practice, to consult social media providers to whom the code is intended to give guidance and such other persons as the Secretary of State considers it appropriate to consult. We will take forward this consultation as part of the Internet Safety Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of what the code of practice will include will be decided following this consultation.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","4727 ; 4729 ; 4757","2017-07-19T13:21:04.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751414/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751414/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will ensure that the code of practice for providers of online social media platforms will include provisions for those providers to fully co-operate with the police on criminal content.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751415","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Digital Economy Act requires the Secretary of State, before issuing a code of practice, to consult social media providers to whom the code is intended to give guidance and such other persons as the Secretary of State considers it appropriate to consult. We will take forward this consultation as part of the Internet Safety Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of what the code of practice will include will be decided following this consultation.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","4727 ; 4728 ; 4757","2017-07-19T13:21:04.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751415/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751415/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she plans to consult stakeholders on the content and nature of the code of practice for social media providers before issuing that code.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751416","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>We keep our preparedness for terrorist attacks under constant review. Since the terrorist attacks in Mumbai in 2008, the Home Office has worked with emergency services to develop a strong, police-led capability to deal with large-scale attacks in the UK. We looked again at our response following the terrorist attacks in Paris in 2015. Those attacks highlighted the challenges any country would face managing multiple, concurrent incidents. In October 2016, Lord Harris published a report on London’s preparedness for a terrorist attack. I recently met with him to discuss its contents.</p><p> </p><p>His report emphasised that the UK’s intelligence agencies and police are “amongst the best in the world”, and highlighted that London’s response to terrorist attack is fast and effective. The Home Office is continuing to work to ensure the highest priorities are given the right resources, and to test and review measures to respond to terrorist attacks. We have revised our risk assessments, and are delivering an uplift in our specialist response capability, including a five year £144 million programme to increase the number of armed officers. Not only are we increasing the number of specialist armed officers but they are now better trained and equipped to deal with the full range of complex attacks.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-20T16:57:56.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751416/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751416/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Metropolitan Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 2727, on what date the most recent assessment was conducted on the capacity of the Metropolitan Police to handle multiple large-scale terrorist attacks.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751417","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>For security reasons, the Home Office cannot comment on the operational deployment of armed policing capabilities.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-20T16:55:49.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751417/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751417/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Greater Manchester Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 2723, how many of the additional 41 armed response vehicles and around 650 armed officers she plans to be based in Manchester.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751418","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Digital Economy Act requires the Secretary of State, before issuing a code of practice, to consult social media providers to whom the code is intended to give guidance and such other persons as the Secretary of State considers it appropriate to consult. We will take forward this consultation as part of the Internet Safety Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of what the code of practice will include will be decided following this consultation.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","4728 ; 4729 ; 4757","2017-07-19T13:21:04.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751418/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751418/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she plans to  include measures to tackle (a) hate conduct and (b) extremist content in the code of practice for providers of online social media platforms.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751419","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-07-20","<p>No members of staff experienced a reduction in their contractual working hours as a result of Dissolution or a decrease in their contractual earnings.</p><p>Staff employed in areas where there was a reduction in work as a result of Dissolution would have had limited opportunity to work non-contractual additional hours or overtime, unless they were helping out areas that were busier because of the Dissolution, such as Digital Services or the New Members Reception Area. Staff continue to receive their contractual monthly salary during periods of lower operational demand. Some staff will have taken annual leave or used up banked hours of Time off in Lieu (TOIL).</p><p>Fluctuations in working hours are managed locally; mainly through flexitime or rostering arrangements. This information is not held centrally.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-07-20T10:05:39.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751419/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751419/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-07-12","House of Commons: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, how many employees experienced a reduction in working hours during the 2017 Dissolution period; and what the (a) smallest, (b) average and (c) largest total reduction in earnings was by proportion of those people who did experience a reduction in working hours.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751420","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-17","<p>Through funding to the Palestinian Market Development Programme, DFID has helped to supply electrical equipment to businesses in the West Bank including computers, and food processing and Laboratory equipment. Through the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation, DFID funded the rehabilitation of a well in the West Bank including the provision of electrical equipment.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-17T16:14:11.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751420/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751420/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-12","West Bank: Electronic Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has supplied any electrical equipment to villages in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","4569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751421","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-19","<p>The total global contribution to the Green Climate Fund (GCF) in each of the last four years has been:</p><p> </p><p>2013: $28 million</p><p>2014: $89 million</p><p>2015: $1,758 million</p><p>2016: $1,570 million</p><p> </p><p>The GCF supports climate-resilient, low-carbon development in developing countries, including by playing a key role in levering finance from multilateral development banks and the private sector for sustainable development. Further information about contributions can be found on the GCF website: <a href="http://www.greenclimate.fund/home" target="_blank">http://www.greenclimate.fund/home</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-19T15:59:59.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751421/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751421/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-12","Green Climate Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the total global contribution to the Green Climate Fund has been in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Graham Stringer","Blackley and Broughton","Graham Stringer","4577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751422","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-18","<p>DFID supports the global elimination of the nematode infection Lymphatic Filariasis. DFID funding has meant that the population at risk from this disease in the 10 African countries and 2 Asian countries supported has fallen by over 85% since 2013. The aim is to achieve full elimination in these 12 countries by 2025.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-18T16:09:36.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751422/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751422/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-12","Parasitic Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress her Department has made on eliminating nematode infections in (a) Africa and (b) the rest of the world.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","4732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751423","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-17","<p>Thank you to the honourable member for her work on this report which highlights the importance of trade for developing countries, and examines the European Economic Partnership Agreements.</p><p>Our first priority is to deliver continuity in our trading arrangements on leaving the EU. The announcement on 25 June, that we will secure existing duty-free access for the world’s poorest countries to UK markets and aim to maintain current access for developing countries, supports this.</p><p>This government remains a long-standing supporter of Economic Partnership Agreements and continues to listen to our partners’ views on how to maximise their benefits.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-17T16:18:57.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751423/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751423/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-12","Africa: Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the findings of the report of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for Africa on the Future of Africa-UK trade and development cooperation relations in the transitional and post-Brexit period, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","4630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751424","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Victims of Overseas Terrorism Compensation Scheme (the Scheme) is a government funded scheme designed to compensate victims injured in terrorist incidents outside the UK on or after 27 November 2012. The rules of the scheme and the value of the payments awarded are set by Parliament and are calculated by reference to a tariff of injuries. The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) administer the Scheme on behalf of the Government and decide the amounts awarded for claims independently of ministers and Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the Scheme can be found at the link below and the tariff of injuries can be found at Annex C to the Scheme: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/243508/9780108512124.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/243508/9780108512124.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>There are two categories of payments under the Scheme:</p><ul><li>injury payments for survivors of a terrorist incident, including physical and mental injuries</li><li>where there is loss of life in a terrorist incident, bereavement awards can be made to certain defined close relatives</li></ul><p> </p><p>The maximum amount payable under the Scheme for</p><p>a) loss of limbs (upper or lower body) is £110,000.</p><p>b) loss of life is £11,000 for a single qualifying relative, or £5,500 each where there is more than one qualifying relative.</p><p> </p><p>Where a victim has been injured, additional payments, such as loss of earnings or special expenses incurred as a direct result of the incident, may also be paid to qualifying claimants.</p><p>Where there is a loss of life additional payments, such as child payments, dependency payments and funeral payments may also be paid to qualifying relatives.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-20T15:26:04.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751424/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751424/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Terrorism: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the maximum compensation payment is under the Victims of Overseas Terrorism Compensation Scheme for (a) loss of limb and (b) loss of life.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","4612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751425","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The HM Prison and Probation Service Executive Committee took the operational decision to cease delivery of the Core and Extended Sex Offender Treatment Programmes and accelerate transition to the Horizon and Kaizen programmes in February 2017 following receipt of the peer reviewed evaluation report and advice from the independent Correctional Services Accreditation and Advisory Panel.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T16:57:02.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751425/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751425/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Sex Offender Treatment Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to his Department's report, Impact evaluation of the prison-based Core Sex Offender Treatment Programme, published on 30 June 2017, when the decision was made to halt that programme.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","4604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751426","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>Ministers were informed of the outcomes of the evaluation and the planned operational response in February 2017. The report was published on 30 June, shortly after the pre-election period.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T16:57:27.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751426/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751426/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Sex Offender Treatment Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the reasons are for the time taken to publish the report, entitled Impact evaluation of the prison-based Core Sex Offender Treatment Programme, published on 30 June 2017.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","4605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751427","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) is considering options to improve its court and tribunal estate in Sunderland and a decision will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The put option currently runs until March 2019 and enables HMCTS to carefully consider all options before a decision is made. No costs have been paid to Sunderland City Council to extend this option since the contract was made.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are in contact with Sunderland City Council and its partners regarding land owned by HMCTS at Farringdon Road to explore the future potential of the land including for the delivery of a public sector hub. HMCTS met with Sunderland City Council and Siglion Developments at noon on 20 December 2016, 11:00 on 15 February 2017 and 10:00 on 21 March 2017.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","4714 ; 4715 ; 4716","2017-07-18T16:43:09.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751427/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751427/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether a decision has been made on the future of Sunderland Court Estate.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","4663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751428","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Employment Tribunal does not record information on the number of successful claimants that are classed as a worker, or an employee, as defined in the Employment Rights Act 1996.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-20T14:31:51.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751428/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751428/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in how many tribunal claims the claimant was successfully classed as a worker in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751429","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>Organisations or individuals that monitor digital devices registered to a person aged 17 or under for the purposes of obtaining information about a third person, must comply with the Data Protection Act's (DPA) eight data protection principles</p><p> </p><p>These include requiring personal data to be processed fairly and lawfully; to be accurate and up-to-date; not to be kept for longer than is necessary; and to be processed in accordance with the rights of the data subjects under the DPA. Failure to comply with the Act is an offence. Further information about these obligations can be found on the ICO's website at:</p><p><a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-19T13:17:58.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751429/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751429/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the Government's policy is on whether a person should be permitted to monitor a digital device registered to a person aged 17 or less for the purposes of obtaining information about a third person in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751430","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>Individuals or organisations that monitor a digital device for the purposes of damaging or stealing data from that person would be in breach of the Data Protection Act (DPA).</p><p> </p><p>The Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) has a range of powers to take action against those who breach the DPA, including the power to serve a Civil Monetary Penalty of up to £500,000. In the most serious cases, section 55 of the DPA makes it an offence for a person to knowingly or recklessly obtain, disclose or procure the disclosure of personal data without the consent of the data controller. The offence is punishable by an unlimited fine.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-19T13:16:00.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751430/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751430/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the Government's policy is on whether a person should be permitted to monitor a digital device for the purposes of damaging or stealing data from that person in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751431","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-17","<p>Community Rehabilitation Companies are contracted to provide ‘through-the-gate’ support to all female offenders on release from custody, and we are engaging with providers about how we can do more to improve the delivery of resettlement services.</p><p>We are committed to ensuring that the complex needs of this vulnerable cohort of offenders are met as they are released from custody, and will provide more details in our strategy for female offenders, which we will publish later this year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-17T17:00:42.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751431/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751431/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Prisoners' Release: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that adequate (a) funding and (b) other support is allocated to female prisoners on release from custodial sentences to assist with their reintegration into society.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","4573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751432","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-20T16:08:54.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751432/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751432/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751432/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Repetitive Strain Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the highest amount paid in compensation has been for a case of repetitive strain injury in a public sector workplace.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","4475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751433","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Protection from Harassment Act 1997 makes it an offence for someone to pursue a course of conduct which amounts to harassment of another and which they know, or ought to know, amounts to harassment of the other.</p><p>Harassment is generally understood to involve improper, oppressive and unreasonable conduct that is targeted at an individual and calculated to alarm them or cause them distress. Depending on the circumstances, repeatedly sending letters or unwanted 'gifts' or other objects to someone or arranging for others to deliver unwanted items to them could constitute harassment.</p><p>Where such behaviour is reported to the police, it would be for them to investigate, for the Crown Prosecution Service to decide whether a prosecution should be brought, and for the court to determine whether the elements of the offence are made out.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-20T14:32:03.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751433/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751433/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the Government's policy is on whether a person should be permitted repeatedly to order goods and services for another person for the purposes of causing distress, anxiety or disrupting that person's daily life in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751434","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The investigation of criminal offences is an operational matter for the police. However, where evidential material, including data held on digital devices, has been seized for the purpose of investigating an offence, any attempt to tamper with, or erase, the material is likely to amount to an offence of perverting the course of justice.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-20T16:01:57.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751434/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751434/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751434/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Criminal Investigation: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the Government's policy is on whether a person should be permitted to erase data remotely while a digital device is being examined by the police or during any other lawful investigation in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751435","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-21","<p>The Information Commissioner's Office's CCTV code of practice provides guidance and advice to CCTV users on how to comply with the Data Protection Act 1998. The guidance can be found at https://ico.org.uk/media/for-organisations/documents/1542/cctv-code-of-practice.pdf</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-21T10:07:36.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751435/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751435/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-12","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the Government's policy is on whether a person should be permitted to install spyware or a webcam or any other device capable of capturing data covertly on another person's property or digital device without the user's agreement or without legal sanction in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751436","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>A consultation stage impact assessment was published in November 2016 and is available at https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/reforming-soft-tissue-injury-claims/. A validated impact assessment detailing the estimated savings to motor insurance premiums arising from the Government’s whiplash reforms, including the data sources and evidence used, will be published alongside the Civil Liability Bill which was announced in the Queen’s Speech.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T14:43:43.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751436/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751436/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will place in the Library his Department's estimates and evidence base for the potential amount of savings to motorists to accrue from proposed reforms to the whiplash claims process.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","4491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751437","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>The Ministry of Justice is finalising a post implementation review of the 2014 bailiff law reforms. We will make a decision on publication in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-25T14:18:09.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751437/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751437/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of the 2014 taking control of goods reform of bailiff law.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751438","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) is considering options to improve its court and tribunal estate in Sunderland and a decision will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The put option currently runs until March 2019 and enables HMCTS to carefully consider all options before a decision is made. No costs have been paid to Sunderland City Council to extend this option since the contract was made.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are in contact with Sunderland City Council and its partners regarding land owned by HMCTS at Farringdon Road to explore the future potential of the land including for the delivery of a public sector hub. HMCTS met with Sunderland City Council and Siglion Developments at noon on 20 December 2016, 11:00 on 15 February 2017 and 10:00 on 21 March 2017.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","4663 ; 4715 ; 4716","2017-07-18T16:43:09.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751438/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751438/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South and the hon. Member for Sunderland Central from the former Courts and Justice Minister on 31 March 2017, how much has been spent on extending the put option on the land at Farringdon Row since the contract was first made.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","4714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751439","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) is considering options to improve its court and tribunal estate in Sunderland and a decision will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The put option currently runs until March 2019 and enables HMCTS to carefully consider all options before a decision is made. No costs have been paid to Sunderland City Council to extend this option since the contract was made.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are in contact with Sunderland City Council and its partners regarding land owned by HMCTS at Farringdon Road to explore the future potential of the land including for the delivery of a public sector hub. HMCTS met with Sunderland City Council and Siglion Developments at noon on 20 December 2016, 11:00 on 15 February 2017 and 10:00 on 21 March 2017.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","4663 ; 4714 ; 4716","2017-07-18T16:43:09.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751439/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751439/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South and the hon. Member for Sunderland Central from the former Courts and Justice Minister on 31 March 2017, on what date and at what time (a) discussions and (b) meetings held between HM Courts and Tribunals Service and (i) Sunderland City Council and (ii) Siglion Developments to discuss a new public sector hub at Keele Square took place in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","4715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751440","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) is considering options to improve its court and tribunal estate in Sunderland and a decision will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The put option currently runs until March 2019 and enables HMCTS to carefully consider all options before a decision is made. No costs have been paid to Sunderland City Council to extend this option since the contract was made.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are in contact with Sunderland City Council and its partners regarding land owned by HMCTS at Farringdon Road to explore the future potential of the land including for the delivery of a public sector hub. HMCTS met with Sunderland City Council and Siglion Developments at noon on 20 December 2016, 11:00 on 15 February 2017 and 10:00 on 21 March 2017.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","4663 ; 4714 ; 4715","2017-07-18T16:43:09.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751440/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751440/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-12","Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South and the hon. Member for Sunderland Central from the former Courts and Justice Minister on 31 March 2017, how much it has cost to extend the put option on the land at Farringdon Row for a further 12 months to March 2018.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","4716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751441","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-19","<p>Following the results of the 2017 General Election, the full year Representative Money allocation for Sinn Fein is:</p><p> </p><p>Main Budget: £161,501.00</p><p>Travel Budget: £3,578.03</p><p> </p><p>The pro-rated figures for the post-election period (i.e. 9 June 2017 to 31 March 2018) are £130,970.55 and £2,901.64 respectively.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for future years will be based on the annual percentage increase of the consumer price index as at the previous December.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-19T10:26:24.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751441/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751441/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-12","Sinn Fein: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to the Answer of 11 July 2017 to Question 2658, on Sinn Fein: finance, if she will publish how much of representative money will be paid to hon. Members elected for Sinn Fein in the 2017-19 parliamentary session; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","4712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751442","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-20","<p><strong>Under a resolution of the House financial assistance is provided to opposition parties represented by Members who have chosen not to take their seats.</strong></p><p><strong><strong>It is the Government's view that this issue <strong>is primarily a matter for the House itself to resolve.</strong></strong></strong></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-20T15:38:49.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751442/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751442/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-12","Sinn Fein: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if the Government will take steps to stop representative money being paid to hon. Members elected for Sinn Féin under the circumstances that those hon. Members refuse to take their seats; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","4678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751443","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-20","<p><strong>Since the resolution of the House of 8 February 2006, up to and including the 2016/17 financial year, the total Main Budget allocation of Representative Money to Sinn Fein has been £1,119,796.</strong></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-20T15:34:57.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751443/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751443/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-12","Sinn Fein: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, how much Representative Money has been paid to hon. Members elected for Sinn Fein since Representative Money was first made available to those hon. Members; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","4680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751444","Scotland Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>We are committed to acting on the decision taken by the British people to leave the EU and to withdraw from the Common Fisheries Policy. As announced in the Queen’s Speech, the Government will introduce a Fisheries Bill, enabling the UK to take responsibility for the access to and management of its fishing waters. The introduction of the Bill is supplemented by our decision to leave the London Fisheries Convention. The UK Government triggered withdrawal from the London Fisheries Convention on 3 July 2017, marking the first step towards building a new domestic fishing policy – one which leads to a more competitive, profitable and sustainable industry for the whole of the UK.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-07-19T14:48:10.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751444/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751444/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-12","Fisheries: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what his policy is on fishing rights in UK waters around Scotland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","4668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751445","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>The United Kingdom's membership of the Green Card system predates our membership of the European Union and is not at risk from withdrawal. Maintaining our current vehicular access to the EU without Green Card checks after we leave is one of a number of issues that will need to be addressed through negotiations. The Government made clear in its White Paper on EU withdrawal that our focus in negotiations will be on ensuring new barriers do not arise from our exit.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-20T13:52:59.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751445/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751445/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that UK citizens travelling in the EU will be able to benefit from the Green Card system as the UK leaves the EU.","true","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","4610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751446","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>In developing its proposals for the Lower Thames Crossing, Highways England examined the impact of incidents on the operation of the Strategic Road Network, and the knock-on effects on the local road network.</p><p> </p><p>These assessments will be further refined as the detailed design for the scheme takes shape.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-20T13:40:17.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751446/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751446/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Lower Thames Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether an assessment has been made of the potential effect on levels of congestion in Gravesham in the event that the (a) existing or (b) proposed new Lower Thames Crossings are heavily congested.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","4684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751447","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>Through traffic modelling and forecasting Highways England has made an assessment of the scheme’s potential effect on levels of congestion at the Dartford Crossing. This is reported in section 4 of the Post-Consultation Scheme Assessment Report Volume 5.</p><p><a href="https://highwaysengland.citizenspace.com/cip/lower-thames-crossing-consultation/supporting_documents/PostConsultation%20Scheme%20Assessment%20Report%20Volume%205.pdf" target="_blank">https://highwaysengland.citizenspace.com/cip/lower-thames-crossing-consultation/supporting_documents/PostConsultation%20Scheme%20Assessment%20Report%20Volume%205.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>As the detailed design for the scheme progresses this will be subject to further assessment and an enhanced traffic model is being developed incorporating the latest travel demand data. This will be used to produce revised traffic volume and congestion forecasts for the local and wider road network, including the Dartford Crossing.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-20T13:35:09.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751447/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751447/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the potential effect on levels of congestion at the Dartford Crossing after the construction of the proposed new Lower Thames Crossing.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","4683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751448","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including the implications for people training for a private pilot’s licence and the UK’s future relationship with the European Aviation Safety Agency system.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the exit negotiations the Government will discuss with the EU and member states how best to continue cooperation in the field of aviation safety and standards. It would not be appropriate to pre-judge the outcome of the negotiations.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-17T14:30:48.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751448/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751448/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Aviation: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on people undertaking training for an EASA private pilot's licence; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","4506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751449","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Department for Transport welcomes the Peninsula Rail Task Force report and the contribution it makes to the consideration of longer term improvements to the rail network in the South West.</p><p> </p><p>We are investing more than £400 million in the network in the South West, including an extra £10 million for the line from Exeter to Newton Abbot via Dawlish that we announced in November 2016. We will continue to work with Network Rail and the Task Force to explore the potential for longer-term improvements in 2019 and beyond.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-20T13:49:29.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751449/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751449/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to respond to the Peninsula Rail Task Force report.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","4465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751450","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>Network Rail is responsible for assessing the effect of peaks and troughs in the company’s annual workload on its capacity to retain skilled staff, as an arm’s length body from government.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-17T13:55:07.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751450/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751450/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Railways: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of peaks and troughs in National Rail's annual workload on its capacity to return skilled staff.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","4522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751451","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>It is for the Greater Manchester Combined Authority to decide how to fund any future extensions to the Manchester Metrolink system. This could include bidding for central Government funding. GMCA has already received funding from the Local Large Majors Fund to help develop a business case for a short extension of the Airport Line to serve the expanded terminal. They plan to bid for scheme funding by the end of the year. The bid will be in competition with a number of other schemes and decisions on which will be funded are to be taken in the New Year.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-20T13:46:42.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751451/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751451/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Manchester Metrolink","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding his Department plans to make available to support the expansion of the Metrolink tram network in Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","4462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751452","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>Highways England and Transport for the North are continuing work to understand the cost and benefits of linking the Manchester and Sheffield areas by tunnel. This will be completed by the autumn, when more information will be made available.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-20T13:23:33.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751452/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751452/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Tunnels: Pennines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent progress his Department has made on the proposed trans-pennine tunnel.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","4463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751453","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>Ensuring a skillful and resilient workforce remains a priority for the Department, and for Network Rail. Network Rail is continuing to invest heavily in the training of its workforce, both in the short term with £44 million invested in capability last year, and in the long term with £60 million invested in the creation of seven state of the art vocational training centres.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure a skill base in the future workforce as well as the present, Network Rail have opened a new apprenticeship centre at Westwood which will by September this year be fully dedicated to the delivery of high quality residential apprenticeships. This will allow Network Rail to meet its commitment to deliver over 4200 apprenticeship new starters within the company by 2022, and supporting the creation of over 2000 within its supply chain.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-17T15:26:33.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751453/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751453/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Railways: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure the availability of a stable and adequate skills base among the workforce in railway occupations.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","4521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751454","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Transpennine Route Upgrade is currently in the design and development phase. An investment decision will be made early next year and target delivery is by December 2022.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-17T15:39:57.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751454/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751454/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether it is his policy to upgrade the Trans-Pennine rail route.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","4545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751455","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The government has no plans to enable seafarers to make telephone calls when they do not have access to UK mobile telephone services.</p><p> </p><p>However, seafarer welfare providers, such as Mission to Seafarers and Apostleship of the Sea, through their centres will often provide discounted phone cards and free wi-fi for foreign seafarers to use. This enables them to call or have ‘skype’ conversations, the preferred option for seafarers, with their friends and families at home when they are in UK ports.</p><p> </p><p>Some major ports and shipowners also allow the seafarers to use their wi-fi for free.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-17T12:32:57.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751455/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751455/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Shipping: Telecommunications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to enable seafarers to make telephone calls when they do not have access to UK mobile telephone services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751456","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>Figures on public sector spend per head of population at a regional level are part of the government’s Country and Regional Analysis (CRA) statistics, and are included below. However, there are significant caveats to be noted regarding the interpretation of these figures for transport spending.</p><p> </p><p>The CRA attempts to allocate expenditure on the basis of which region benefits from the spend, rather than where it is made. However, this can be challenging as expenditure in one part of the country may actually benefit a different area, and this affectsmotorways, trunk roads, and the railways. For example, whilst spending on a local hospital will predominantly benefit those who live in that area, spending on a motorway or railway line will benefit not just those living nearby but also those travelling from and to other areas across the country. Whilst the Department seeksto record rail funding across the regions based on which passengers benefit, allocations are inevitably fairly imprecise.</p><p> </p><p>Similarly, in recording spending on a per capita basis (i.e. per head of resident population), the calculation for London does not account for the large number of daily commuters, visitors and tourists who use and benefit from the roads and public transport networks, but who are not London residents. In particular, as the main international gateway into the country, London is the location for a range of transport investments which are designed to serve passengers well beyond the local resident population.</p><p> </p><p>The above caveats should be taken into account when looking at the CRA figures for regional Government expenditure on transport. The figures for 2015-16 relating to locations (b), (c) and (d) from the above request are shown in the table below. This information is published for government office regions only, and therefore is unavailable for (a) Liverpool City Region.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Table 1. Government expenditure on transport per head of population by region</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total transport spend per capita</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>£401</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£973</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£365</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source:</p><p>HM Treasury Country and Regional Analysis (CRA) 2016</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-17T15:29:25.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751456/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751456/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Transport: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what comparative assessment he has made of public spending per capita on transport infrastructure in (a) the Liverpool City Region, (b) the North West, (c) London and (d) the South East.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751457","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government intends later this year to set out its priorities for investment in train services and infrastructure in the next five year Control Period from 2019. This will be informed by advice from the rail industry, Transport for the North and other stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that every part of Britain benefits from our investment in the railways. Improvements in rail services can be delivered by new trains and a range of infrastructure improvements. The Government keeps under close review what options will ensure the maximum value to taxpayers, passengers and freight users.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-17T15:01:58.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751457/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751457/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to commission new rail infrastructure in the North of England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751458","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The consultation on the draft Airports National Policy Statement closed on 25 May, and we are analysing the tens of thousands of responses received. The Government will set out the next steps in the process in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Airports Commission published growth forecasts for regional airports for the three shortlisted schemes. (https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/439687/strategic-fit-updated-forecasts.pdf). The Department has undertaken an economic assessment of the impact of a new runway at Heathrow at a national level, taking account of all areas of the UK.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-17T14:58:07.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751458/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751458/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he will plans to make a decision on expansion of capacity at Heathrow Airport; and what assessment he has made of the effect of such expansion on (a) Liverpool airport and (b) other airports.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751459","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The traffic lights at junctions 4, 5 and 6 on the M54 do not affect the flow of traffic on the M54 itself and are not the responsibility of Highways England. The surrounding roads at all three of these junctions are managed and maintained by Telford and Wrekin Council. They will be best placed to advise on the effects these lights have on traffic flows on the surrounding roads.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-17T14:22:58.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751459/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751459/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","M54: Traffic Lights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will discuss with Highways England the effect on traffic flow of the traffic lights at junctions (a) 4, (b) 5 and (c) 6 of the M54.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","4575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751460","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>Through the Strategic Freight Network fund, the Government is currently funding a number of investments to improve rail freight connectivity to this Port. The Government intends later this year to set out its priorities for investment in train services and infrastructure in England and Wales in the next five year Control Period from 2019. This will be informed by advice from the rail industry, Transport for the North and other stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>Ports such as Liverpool are making significant private sector investments in infrastructure to prepare for freight growth. It is economically important that inland transport networks are also able to handle such future freight growth. That is why the Department is currently examining the sufficiency of port access and connectivity in England and to identify where connectivity improvements could support economic growth.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-17T12:36:38.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751460/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751460/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","Liverpool Port: Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the need for additional rail infrastructure at the Port of Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751461","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The British Transport Police’s counter terrorism capability, forms an integral part of its policing of the railways, and is therefore not readily distinguishable within the overall costs of policing. The funding required to deliver it is met by the rail industry, and is regularly reviewed to ensure that it continues to provide a safe rail network for its staff and the travelling public. The Department has not provided any direct funding to the BTP during the current or the last financial year.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-17T16:25:25.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751461/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751461/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","British Transport Police: Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what additional expenditure the British Transport Police has incurred on counter terrorism in (a) 2017-18 to date and (b) 2016-17; and what additional funding his Department provided to that organisation for counter-terror operations in those periods.","true","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","4754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751462","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-17","<p>This is an operational matter for the Chief Constable. We have been informed by the British Transport Police (BTP) that there are no current plans to change the number of BTP control centres.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-17T16:28:18.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751462/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751462/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-12","British Transport Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to change the number of British Transport Police control centres.","true","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","4755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751463","Wales Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>Ministers and I have regular discussions with HM Treasury on targeted interventions to support economic growth in Wales. These include City and Growth Deals such as the deals we have already announced for Cardiff and Swansea and the deal we have committed to for North Wales which we are discussing with local partners. Wales also benefits from the financial security of the new funding settlement put in place by the fiscal framework we agreed with the Welsh Government last year to guarantee a fair level of funding for the long-term.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-20T10:59:10.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751463/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751463/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-12","Finance: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has had discussions or corresponded with HM Treasury on funding for Wales since the announcement of the Government's agreement with the Democratic Unionist Party.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751464","Wales Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>I have frequent discussions and correspond regularly with my Cabinet colleagues on the steel industry in Wales. We are working with the sector, the unions and devolved administrations to support the steel sector develop a long-term viable solution for the steel industry in Wales and across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-20T11:00:18.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751464/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751464/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-12","Iron and Steel: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has had discussions or corresponded with Cabinet Colleagues on measures to support the steel industry in Wales since 8 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751465","Wales Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>I have regular discussions with Ministerial colleagues about all matters pertaining to Wales. I will work closely with the Department for Work and Pensions to ensure that the interests of staff and customers are paramount as plans are finalised.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-20T11:04:21.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751465/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751465/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Newport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has had discussions or corresponded with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on his Department's service centre in Newport.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751466","Wales Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>I have regular discussions with Ministerial colleagues about matters pertaining to Wales. The Government's position on the tolls is very simple and straightforward; we will abolish them.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-20T10:57:26.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751466/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751466/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-12","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if he will publish the details of any correspondence or discussions he has had with HM Treasury on ending the Severn tolls.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751467","Wales Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>Wales Office Ministers regularly visit Parliamentary Constituencies in Wales. In each instance, the respective honourable Member is notified of the visit. Details of Ministerial visits and meetings are published on the Wales Office website, and in Quarterly Ministerial Transparency Returns. In addition, visits and meetings conducted in support of the Wales Office Business Plan are published in the Wales Office Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p>Wales Office Ministers are always keen to receive invitation requests from honourable Members.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-19T14:45:51.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751467/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751467/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-12","Domestic Visits: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which parliamentary constituencies in Wales he has visited in each month since June 2016.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751468","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-19T12:00:44.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751468/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751468/answer","PQ4535 FINAL .pdf","UKSA Response to PQ4535","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751468/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-12","Young People: Zero Hours Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information his Department holds on the number of 18 to 25-year olds who are on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mhairi Black","4535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751469","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-19","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Automatic enrolment into workplace pensions was introduced to enable more people to save for their retirement. So far over 8 million people have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension, reversing the decline in private pension saving, including amongst younger workers, seen in the decade before the reforms were introduced in 2012.</p><p><br>In March this year, the Office for National Statistics published an estimate that around 160,000 employees aged 16-21 and 2.7 million employees aged 22-29 were contributing to a workplace pension in 2016</p><p> </p><p>We are looking at how we can build on this success over the longer term. Our current review of automatic enrolment is looking at the existing coverage of the policy and the needs of those not currently benefiting; strengthening the evidence base concerning future contributions; and how we can encourage greater personal ownership of work place pension saving, including by young people. The Review will report at the end of 2017.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","4534","2017-07-19T10:11:31.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751469/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751469/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Pensions: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate he has made of the number of young people who are saving for a pension.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mhairi Black","4533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751470","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-19","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Automatic enrolment into workplace pensions was introduced to enable more people to save for their retirement. So far over 8 million people have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension, reversing the decline in private pension saving, including amongst younger workers, seen in the decade before the reforms were introduced in 2012.</p><p><br>In March this year, the Office for National Statistics published an estimate that around 160,000 employees aged 16-21 and 2.7 million employees aged 22-29 were contributing to a workplace pension in 2016</p><p> </p><p>We are looking at how we can build on this success over the longer term. Our current review of automatic enrolment is looking at the existing coverage of the policy and the needs of those not currently benefiting; strengthening the evidence base concerning future contributions; and how we can encourage greater personal ownership of work place pension saving, including by young people. The Review will report at the end of 2017.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","4533","2017-07-19T10:11:31.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751470/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751470/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Pensions: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to encourage young people to save for a pension; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mhairi Black","4534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751471","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>DWP does not have its own definitions of (a) flexible worker and (b) flexible working.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T10:58:50.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751471/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751471/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what definition his Department uses of (a) flexible worker and (b) flexible working.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","4509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751472","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Throughout the development of our proposals, the Department has been mindful of its duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010. An equality analysis of the potential impact on staff and customers in Liverpool was informed by statistical analysis of population data, local knowledge and consultation.</p><p> </p><p>Any issues identified were taken fully into consideration and helped to inform our final plans which were announced on 5 July 2017.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T10:56:07.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751472/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751472/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment he has carried out of the effect of proposals to close job centres in Liverpool; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","4515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751473","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>This Department does not fund public health or ‘Paupers’ funerals.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-17T16:05:36.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751473/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751473/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Public Health Funerals: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many paupers funerals his Department has funded in Wales in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751474","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) estimates that it receives approximately 31.8 million calls from mobile telephones per year. We are unable to determine how many of these calls were made from Pay as You Go mobile telephones. Any charges that apply to these calls will be set by the customer’s telephone or mobile operator however they are never more than the cost of a geographic number, which are those with 01 and 02 dialling codes.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-17T16:20:31.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751474/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751474/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on members of the public who contact his Department of the cost of calling 0345 numbers from Pay as You Go mobile telephones.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","4549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751475","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>The department does not collect such specific complaints data.</p><p> </p><p>To obtain this information we would need to examine individual complaints grouped under the broader categories of “You were wrong about my entitlement” and “You paid me the wrong amount”.</p><p> </p><p>Owing to the volume of complaints that will need to be examined to obtain this information it can only be collated at disproportionate cost to the department.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-17T16:13:22.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751475/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751475/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints his Department received on claimants whose legacy benefits were not protected following their transfer to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","4548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751476","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Claimants currently moving from existing benefits to Universal Credit will only do so because they will have had a significant change in their circumstances that would previously have triggered a new claim to an existing benefit or tax credit. In such circumstances they would always have had their entitlement calculated based on the rules of their new benefit. This principle has been maintained for those moving to Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>We have announced that we will be starting managed migration of existing benefit claimants to Universal Credit from July 2019 and that this will be completed by March 2022. We have committed that we will pay transitional protection to all claimants who move to Universal Credit as part of this process and whose entitlement is less than their entitlement to existing benefits and tax credits.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","4552","2017-07-17T10:57:27.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751476/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751476/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of claimants whose legacy benefits have not been protected following a transfer to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","4551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751477","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Claimants currently moving from existing benefits to Universal Credit will only do so because they will have had a significant change in their circumstances that would previously have triggered a new claim to an existing benefit or tax credit. In such circumstances they would always have had their entitlement calculated based on the rules of their new benefit. This principle has been maintained for those moving to Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>We have announced that we will be starting managed migration of existing benefit claimants to Universal Credit from July 2019 and that this will be completed by March 2022. We have committed that we will pay transitional protection to all claimants who move to Universal Credit as part of this process and whose entitlement is less than their entitlement to existing benefits and tax credits.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","4551","2017-07-17T10:57:28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751477/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751477/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department takes to ensure that people who have not retained the legacy benefits that they are entitled to can have such benefits reinstated swiftly.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","4552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751478","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>The information requested is not available. Data will become available as this policy area matures.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-17T14:01:39.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751478/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751478/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Universal Credit: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many young people between 18 and 21 years old have (a) applied for and (b) been granted exemptions to ensure entitlement to the housing costs element of universal credit since 1 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","4560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751479","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Figures for consolatory payments to resident parents for the Child Maintenance Service and for the Child Support Agency are provided below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Financial Reporting Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Consolatory Payments Made to Resident Parent</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>(Child Maintenance Service)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>*Dec 2014 to March 2015</p></td><td><p>130</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016</p></td><td><p>595</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/2017</p></td><td><p>835</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April to June 2017</p></td><td><p>250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Financial Reporting Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Consolatory Payments Made</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>(Child Support Agency) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/2010</p></td><td><p>7,920</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/2011</p></td><td><p>5,405</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/2012</p></td><td><p>4,130</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>4,670</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>4,245</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>2,835</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016</p></td><td><p>1,725</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/2017</p></td><td><p>910</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April to June 2017</p></td><td><p>130</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ol><li>Figures are rounded to the nearest 5.</li><li>We have interpreted resident parent to be Receiving Parent for the Child Maintenance Service and Parent with Care for the Child Support Agency.</li><li>“*” for the Child Maintenance Service for 2014/15 indicates it’s not a full year.</li><li>Figures for the Child Support Agency are for all parents as we are unable to show payments purely to the resident parent.</li></ol>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-17T14:08:11.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751479/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751479/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times in each year of their operation the Child Maintenance Service and its predecessor bodies have paid a consolatory payment to a resident parent.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751480","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Officials have regular discussions with a wide variety of groups representing scheme customers and suppliers. In recent years such organisations representing deaf customers' issues have included:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Royal Association of Deaf people</li><li>Action on Hearing Loss</li><li>British Deaf Association</li><li>Signature</li><li>Deaf AtW</li><li>UK Council on Deafness</li><li>Association of Sign Language Interpreters</li><li>National Union of British Sign Language Interpreters</li><li>Scottish Association of Sign Language Interpreters</li></ul><p> </p><p>In addition Access to Work officials have had many more discussions with organisations who represent the deaf community’s interests as part of a broader agenda as well as presenting updates to the department’s operational stakeholder engagement forum (OSEF) which acts as a broader forum for Access to Work to engage with various groups of stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2015 the Government published an Equality Analysis of the impact of the reforms to Access to Work, which may be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/426416/future-of-access-to-work-equality-analysis.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/426416/future-of-access-to-work-equality-analysis.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>From April this year the Cap is set at £42,100 per annum, calculated at one-and-a-half times the prevailing annual average earnings figure. There are no plans to alter the current uprating mechanism. We will be reflecting on Access to Work as we continue our work stemming from the recent Green Paper.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","4666","2017-07-17T16:12:17.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751480/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751480/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Access to Work Programme: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the current funding cap of £42,100 on the (a) number of people from the deaf community accessing the access to work scheme and (b) levels of funding available for members of the deaf community; and whether he has plans to change the level of that cap.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","4667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751481","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Officials have regular discussions with a wide variety of groups representing scheme customers and suppliers. In recent years such organisations representing deaf customers' issues have included:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Royal Association of Deaf people</li><li>Action on Hearing Loss</li><li>British Deaf Association</li><li>Signature</li><li>Deaf AtW</li><li>UK Council on Deafness</li><li>Association of Sign Language Interpreters</li><li>National Union of British Sign Language Interpreters</li><li>Scottish Association of Sign Language Interpreters</li></ul><p> </p><p>In addition Access to Work officials have had many more discussions with organisations who represent the deaf community’s interests as part of a broader agenda as well as presenting updates to the department’s operational stakeholder engagement forum (OSEF) which acts as a broader forum for Access to Work to engage with various groups of stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2015 the Government published an Equality Analysis of the impact of the reforms to Access to Work, which may be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/426416/future-of-access-to-work-equality-analysis.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/426416/future-of-access-to-work-equality-analysis.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>From April this year the Cap is set at £42,100 per annum, calculated at one-and-a-half times the prevailing annual average earnings figure. There are no plans to alter the current uprating mechanism. We will be reflecting on Access to Work as we continue our work stemming from the recent Green Paper.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","4667","2017-07-17T16:12:17.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751481/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751481/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Access to Work Programme: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with organisations representing the deaf community on the effectiveness of the access to work scheme.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","4666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751482","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government welcomes the Work and Pensions Select Committee report and is carefully considering its recommendations. We will submit the Government response in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-17T14:13:06.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751482/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751482/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-12","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 82 of the 14th Report of the Work and Pensions Committee of 2016-17, Child Maintenance Service, HC 587, whether he plans to implement the recommendation on reinstating provisions for parents to challenge child maintenance awards on the grounds of assets and lifestyle inconsistent with income.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751483","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013 (CCRs), which came into force on 13 June 2014, requires the Secretary of State to review the regulations 5 years after they have come into force. These implemented the EU Consumer Rights Directive and the Department worked closely with OFCOM with regard to the characteristics of a basic rate number. The Department will review the Regulations, including the provision of basic rate customer helplines, by 13 June 2019.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:25:46.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751483/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751483/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751483/answer/previousversion/5091","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","Telephone Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress he has made on the planned review of the implementation of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations with regard to the provision of basic rate customer helplines.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","4647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751484","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>We do not hold specific information on UK ownership given the breadth of the sector and related supply chain. There has been significant overseas investment into offshore wind in the UK. Bloomberg New Energy Finance reported that in 2016 the UK led Europe for the third successive year, with investment of $25.9bn, up 2% year on year percentage increase in investment in the UK in clean energy.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-26T09:13:47.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751484/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751484/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751484/answer/previousversion/5078","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of the UK's offshore wind sector is owned by UK investors and companies.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","4643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751485","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>In line with the Government’s response to the Waterson review, National Trading Standards have been tasked with investigating potential enforcement cases against sellers and secondary ticketing websites that do not comply with legislation from within their current and forthcoming annual budgets.</p><p>The National Trading Standards Board have allocated £300,000 towards investigation work on ticketing for this current financial year.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T16:57:08.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751485/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751485/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","National Trading Standards Board","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what additional funding he has provided to the National Trading Standards Board to implement the recommendations of the Waterson Review accepted by the Government in its response on 13 March 2017; and what that funding will be spent on in the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","4587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751486","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Government is keen to see greater corporate responsibility on the part of employers and to encourage the public sector, charities and businesses to consider their impact on society. Employer-supported volunteering can help to build stronger communities and a stronger economy, by helping charities and community groups to do more and by creating a more motivated and productive workforce. Many public sector organisations and businesses already run impressive volunteering programmes.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-20T16:08:15.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751486/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751486/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751486/answer/previousversion/5081","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","Voluntary Work: Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to introduce a new workplace entitlement to volunteering leave for three days a year.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","4709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751487","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Falklands oil &amp; gas industry is managed by the Falkland Islands Government. Any assessment of the opportunities, therefore, is the responsibility of the Falkland Islands Government.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-17T16:13:49.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751487/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751487/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-12","Falkland Islands: Fossil Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the potential opportunities for the hydrocarbon industry in the Exclusive Economic Zone of the Falkland Islands.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","4743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751488","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>The government is currently considering next steps in light of responses to the consultation.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T13:20:32.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751488/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751488/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751488/answer/previousversion/5065","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","Gratuities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57781, when his Department plans to announce the outcome of the tips, gratuities, cover and service charges: proposals for further action consultation which ended on 27 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","4517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751489","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>Growth Deals provide funds to Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) for projects that benefit the local area and economy. New Anglia LEP’s total Growth Deal with Government is worth £290.8m and is supporting a number of key local infrastructure projects in Suffolk. This includes a commitment of £5m for a Beccles relief road, a feasibility study on the options of a third river crossing in Lowestoft and £5m to support superfast broadband roll-out across the county.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T15:11:29.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751489/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751489/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","Infrastructure: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what fiscal measures his Department is taking to support infrastructure projects in Suffolk.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","4479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751490","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>I have now done so.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:08:54.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751490/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751490/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-12","Products: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2017 to Question 1324, when he plans to publish the answer referred to.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","4544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751491","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Arfon to the answer I gave him on 12 July 2017, UIN: 3614.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-21T12:53:41.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751491/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751491/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-12","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, to what extent each of the devolved administrations will be included, involved in and consulted on future trade deals.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","4468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751492","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-20","<p>As part of the process of reviewing the Inter-Governmental Agreement between the UK and the US that implements FATCA in the UK, my officials have raised a wide range of issues with the US Treasury and the IRS, including the obligations placed by the US on the non-life insurance industry.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","4634 ; 4702","2017-07-20T14:03:52.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751492/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751492/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Taxation: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has made to his counterpart in the US on the effect on UK financial services businesses of complying with the US Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","4703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751493","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-20","<p>As part of the process of reviewing the Inter-Governmental Agreement between the UK and the US that implements FATCA in the UK, my officials have raised a wide range of issues with the US Treasury and the IRS, including the obligations placed by the US on the non-life insurance industry.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","4634 ; 4703","2017-07-20T14:03:52.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751493/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751493/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Taxation: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the US on repealing the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act and exempting non-life insurance services from the remit of that Act as part of ongoing trade discussions between the UK and US.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","4702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751494","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-19","<p>The UK has separate agreements in place with France and Belgium that determine the status and rights of nationals employed at juxtaposed controls, including customs areas. These agreements are separate from the UK’s membership of the EU and will remain in force after we leave.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-19T14:26:08.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751494/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751494/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-12","Customs Officers: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017 what rights will be accorded to staff at customs points who work in the UK but live in another EU member state.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751495","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-20","<p>Children of EU citizens who hold settled status and are born in the UK will automatically acquire British citizenship. EU resident parents who arrived before the specified date, but who need to apply for permission to stay post-exit in order to meet the five year residence requirement, will also need to apply for the same permission on behalf of their child when their child is born.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-20T13:35:55.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751495/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751495/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-12","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether a child born after the specified date to a lawful EU resident who arrived in the UK before the specified date will be eligible for settled status.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751496","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>As the Government’s policy paper (C9464) sets out, we recognise that the cost of the new scheme will be important for EU nationals. The UK intends to set fees at a reasonable level.</p><p>We have been clear that EU citizens will enjoy all of their current residence rights until we exit from the EU, and that they will have time to secure their new status post-exit. However, the Government does intend to introduce a voluntary scheme to enable eligible EU citizens to apply for their permission to stay and residence document before the UK’s withdrawal from the EU. This will enable them to obtain their UK immigration status at an early stage, should they wish to do so, in order to ensure as smooth and efficient process as possible for EU residents here.</p><p>Details of the new scheme are the subject of ongoing negotiations with the EU and therefore will be set out in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","4707","2017-07-17T16:44:26.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751496/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751496/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much it will cost EU citizens wishing to register to remain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","4706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751497","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>As the Government’s policy paper (C9464) sets out, we recognise that the cost of the new scheme will be important for EU nationals. The UK intends to set fees at a reasonable level.</p><p>We have been clear that EU citizens will enjoy all of their current residence rights until we exit from the EU, and that they will have time to secure their new status post-exit. However, the Government does intend to introduce a voluntary scheme to enable eligible EU citizens to apply for their permission to stay and residence document before the UK’s withdrawal from the EU. This will enable them to obtain their UK immigration status at an early stage, should they wish to do so, in order to ensure as smooth and efficient process as possible for EU residents here.</p><p>Details of the new scheme are the subject of ongoing negotiations with the EU and therefore will be set out in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","4706","2017-07-17T16:44:26.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751497/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751497/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-12","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for details to be made available to EU citizens on how to register to remain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","4707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751498","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-21","<p>We have not met jointly. We are committed to full engagement with the Government of Gibraltar through the Joint Ministerial Council (Gibraltar EU Negotiations) which has met three times including most recently on Monday 17 July. We have been clear in our conversations with Spain that Gibraltar is covered by our exit negotiations and we will have full regard for their interests.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-21T10:21:44.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751498/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751498/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-12","Gibraltar: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he has met jointly with representatives of Gibraltar and Spain to discuss the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","4734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751499","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-18","<p>The agreement on Citizens’ Rights will be enshrined in UK law and enforceable through the UK judicial system, up to and including the Supreme Court. We are also ready to make commitments in the Withdrawal Agreement which will have the status of international law. We are committed to rules-based international order and the UK takes seriously the responsibilities we have signed up to via international agreements.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-18T12:50:44.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751499/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751499/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-12","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 11 July 2017 to Question 3597, on immigration, how individuals will be able to enforce within and outside the UK the rights contained within the Withdrawal Agreement which will have the status of international law.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751500","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-21","<p>The Government has been clear from the start that the devolved administrations should be fully engaged in our preparations to leave the EU. The Secretary of State has had a number of bilateral discussions with the Scottish and Welsh Governments as we have moved into the negotiation phase and we are committed to positive and productive engagement going forward. In the absence of an Executive, we have also engaged at an official level with the Northern Ireland Civil Service.</p><p>Over the summer, we anticipate there will be regular and sustained bilateral discussions with officials from the devolved administrations, reporting back to Ministers at regular intervals to ensure sufficient progress is being made. There is also a place for multilateral meetings, and we will take that forward as and when it is appropriate.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-21T10:13:27.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751500/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751500/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-12","Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotiations) will next meet.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","4456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753087","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>The time taken by the Valuation Office Agency to process rateable value appeals depends on a number of factors. These include the complexity of a case or whether it proceeds to a hearing by the independent Valuation Tribunal. Some cases can be held up in litigation or placed on hold at the ratepayer's request. The Government has reformed the appeals process to ensure that genuine appeals can be dealt with more quickly.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-18T14:45:02.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753087/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753087/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the time taken by the Valuation Office Agency to process rateable value appeals.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","900568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753088","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>Since 2010, the headline corporation tax rate has been cut from 28 to 19 percent.</p><p> </p><p>Despite that, onshore corporation tax receipts have increased by over 50 percent, from £36.2 billion in 2010-11 to £55.1 billion in 2016-17.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-18T14:46:59.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753088/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753088/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what effect the reduction in corporation tax rates has had on receipts from that tax.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","900569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753089","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government continues to carry out a significant amount of work to assess the economic and fiscal impacts of leaving the EU.</p><p>The detail of future UK-EU arrangements is now subject to negotiations with the EU. As we enter into negotiations, we will work hard to seek the best possible deal for the UK.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-18T14:43:43.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753089/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753089/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the tax revenue implications of the UK leaving the EU on trade (a) under WTO rules and (b) as part of the Single Market and Customs Union.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","900570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753090","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>Since 2010, the headline corporation tax rate has been cut from 28 to 19 percent.</p><p> </p><p>Despite that, onshore corporation tax receipts have increased by over 50 percent, from £36.2 billion in 2010-11 to £55.1 billion in 2016-17.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-18T14:48:56.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753090/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753090/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what effect the reduction in corporation tax rates has had on receipts from that tax.","false","Biography information for Alex Burghart","Brentwood and Ongar","Alex Burghart","900566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753091","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>The independent Financial Policy Committee, was set up by the government to assess and mitigate financial stability risks. The FPC recently published in June the Financial Stability Report (FSR) which assessed recent trends in the consumer credit market including car finance. The FSR noted that consumer credit has been growing rapidly but that loss rates on consumer credit lending are low at present.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-18T16:04:03.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753091/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753091/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Loans: Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for the wider economy of the trend in the take-up of personal contract purchase plans for cars.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","900567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753092","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>Since 2010, the deficit has been reduced by three-quarters. However, as the OBR’s Fiscal Risks Report published last week shows, the public finances remain vulnerable and it’s important for this country to bring down its levels of debt.</p><p>That is why the government has committed to reduce the structural deficit to below 2% and get debt falling as a share of GDP by 2020-21, guiding the public finances back to balance by the middle of the next decade.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-07-18T13:31:19.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753092/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753092/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-12","Public Sector Debt","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress is being made on reducing the deficit.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","900565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750528","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>It is the Government’s intention to lay the remedial order, which will allow single people to apply for a parental order in a surrogacy arrangement, after the summer recess. The order will include a provision to allow for retrospective application for a parental order by single people.</p><p> </p><p>The Government supports the inclusion of a review of surrogacy legislation in the Law Commission’s 13<sup>th</sup> programme of law reform. The Department has not made any alternative plans for a review of surrogacy but would consider options carefully, if, for any reason, the Law Commission decides not to proceed.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL661","2017-07-19T13:51:00.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750528/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750528/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answers by Nicola Blackwood MP on 8 March (HC66737) and by Philip Dunne MP on 27 June (HC510), whether a remedial order to allow single parents to apply for a parental order following surrogacy will be laid before Parliament after the summer recess; and if so, whether that order will operate retrospectively once approved.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750529","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>It is the Government’s intention to lay the remedial order, which will allow single people to apply for a parental order in a surrogacy arrangement, after the summer recess. The order will include a provision to allow for retrospective application for a parental order by single people.</p><p> </p><p>The Government supports the inclusion of a review of surrogacy legislation in the Law Commission’s 13<sup>th</sup> programme of law reform. The Department has not made any alternative plans for a review of surrogacy but would consider options carefully, if, for any reason, the Law Commission decides not to proceed.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL660","2017-07-19T13:51:01.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750529/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750529/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the conclusion of the report by the Surrogacy UK Working Group on Surrogacy Law, Surrogacy in the UK: Myth bashing and reform, published in November 2015, whether they continue to support the inclusion of a review of the law on surrogacy in the Law Commission's 13th programme of law reform; and whether they will commit to their own review of the law on surrogacy if the Law Commission does not take this forward.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750530","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>The specification for the new trains for HS2 Phase1 is currently being developed and will form part of the invitation to tender for rolling stock to be issued in 2018.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-20T10:40:17.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750530/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750530/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of their specification for the new trains for HS2, what is the maximum electrical current draw per train permissible on (1) HS2 infrastructure, and (2) existing Network Rail infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750531","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>HS2 Ltd and Network Rail are cooperatively engaged in determining the future power supply requirements for Network Rail routes over which HS2 services will operate. This work will take account of the requirements of all users of the routes and will identify the scope and timing requirements of any modifications that are identified as necessary. The output of these discussions will inform decisions around the planning and funding of any proposed works.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-20T10:43:02.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750531/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750531/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what modifications to the power supply (1) are planned, and (2) have been funded, to facilitate operation of HS2 services on Network Rail infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750532","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Government recognises that regional air connectivity across the UK is very important and airports support regional economies, create skilled employment opportunities and enable business and leisure travel. However, the UK aviation market operates in a competitive, commercial environment; it is therefore for airlines to determine which routes they operate.</p><p> </p><p>The Government provides financial support through Public Service Obligations (PSO) in a limited number of cases to ensure that all regions of the UK maintain air connectivity to the capital, which include:</p><p> </p><ul><li>£2.85million for a two-year PSO route between Dundee and London Stansted Airport;</li><li>£2.87million for a four-year PSO route between Newquay Cornwall and London Gatwick Airport; and</li><li>£3.78 million for a two-year PSO route between City of Derry Airport to London Stansted Airport</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Government is also committed to developing a new Aviation Strategy and we will be setting out our proposed approach in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-19T13:39:00.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750532/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750532/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to esure that there are adequate air transport connections between major cities in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750533","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>As set out in the Government’s General Election manifesto we are committed to the implementation of the legacy bodies in the Stormont House Agreement. Much progress has been made on taking these forward and the next phase is to move to public consultation. Following developments in the recent talks, the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland is reflecting carefully on the next steps for taking forward the legacy consultation.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T11:06:06.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750533/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750533/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to deal with issues connected with the legacy of the conflict in Northern Ireland should political parties there fail to reach agreement on the formation of an Executive.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750534","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Office for National Statistics publishes annual statistics on suicide registrations for the United Kingdom, including age-specific suicide rates by five-year age groups. A table attached provides statistics for suicides in people aged 10-14 and 15-19 in the UK between 1981 and 2015, the latest data available, is attached due to the size of the data.</p><p> </p><p>The Department leads delivery of the Cross-Government Suicide Prevention Strategy for England. Suicide prevention is a devolved matter in other UK countries.</p><p> </p><p>The National Confidential Inquiry into Suicide and Homicide by People with Mental Illness, which is commissioned by NHS England and supported by the Department, published a thematic review in 2016, Suicide by Children and Young People in England. The report identified ten common themes relating to suicides by people under 20 years of age:</p><p> </p><p>- family factors such as mental illness;</p><p>- abuse and neglect;</p><p>- bereavement and experience of suicide;</p><p>- bullying;</p><p>- suicide-related internet use;</p><p>- academic pressures, especially related to exams;</p><p>- social isolation or withdrawal;</p><p>- physical health conditions that may have social impact;</p><p>- alcohol and illicit drugs; and</p><p>- mental ill health, self-harm and suicidal ideas.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-07-19T15:11:50.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750534/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750534/answer","HL666 formatted table.docx","Suicides in UK 1981-2015 10-19 year olds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750534/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the level of suicide among teenagers in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750535","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>We do not routinely collect information about how many local Troubled Families programmes include the prevention of parents' relationship instability. My department is working closely with the Department for Work and Pensions to help local authorities delivering the Troubled Families Programme do more to tackle worklessness and parental conflict.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-19T15:28:20.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750535/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750535/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 20 March (HL 5929), (1) how many local authorities, through the Troubled Families Programme, have included within their aims (where appropriate) the prevention of parents' relationship instability, and (2) what plans they have to ensure that the Troubled Families Programme takes into account the findings set out in Improving lives: Helping Working Families on the impact of parental worklessness, and associated conflict, on families.","false","Biography information for Lord Farmer",,"Lord Farmer","HL667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750536","Home Office","false","2017-07-31","<p>Rule 17 of the Detention Centre Rules 2001 permits detainees to engage in paid activities while in detention and is provided as a means to occupy detainees and alleviate boredom.</p><p>It is not permitted contractually for private service providers to use the detainee paid work scheme to replace staffing obligations and there are no savings or efficiencies realised by the private service providers or the Home Office from the option for detainees to work in this voluntary scheme.</p><p>Management information shows that for the period 1 April 2016 to 31 March 2017 detainees in immigration removal centres undertook a total of 887,073 hours of paid work, with payments made to detainees totalling £887,565. This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-31T14:23:50.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750536/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750536/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the reply by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 4 July (HL Deb, col 789) regarding rates of pay for work undertaken by immigration removal centre detainees, how much was paid to detainees in aggregate, and for how many hours' work, in the last year for which figures are available; whether the savings in the running costs of immigration removal centres represented by detainees undertaking work which would otherwise have been paid at commercial rates accrue to (1) HM Treasury, (2) to the immigration removal centre providers, or (3) other bodies or agencies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750537","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-25","<p>We regularly raise the importance of compliance with International Humanitarian Law with the Saudi Arabian Government. Saudi Arabia has publicly stated that it is investigating reports of alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law through the Coalition’s Joint Incidents Assessment Team (JIAT), and that lessons will be acted upon.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-07-25T13:37:18.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750537/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750537/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia about the bombing of civilians in Yeman; and what response they received.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750538","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-20","<p>At the recent UN Oceans Conference the UK made several voluntary commitments, including signing up to the UN’s CleanSeas campaign. This programme aims to transform habits, practices, standards and policies around the globe to dramatically reduce marine litter and the harm it causes.</p><p>The UK Government has undertaken several key actions to protect the marine environment from marine litter which are set out in the Marine Strategy Part Three. Recent additional actions include the publication of the National Litter Strategy for England and our plans to ban microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products. We also work with neighbouring countries to address this issue, particularly through the OSPAR Regional Action Plan on marine litter.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-07-20T15:10:06.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750538/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750538/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-11","Seas and Oceans: Plastics","2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the UN Oceans Conference on 5–9 June and the Council of the European Union Environment Council on 19 June, what plans they have to reduce, and if possible eliminate, the pollution of oceans, seas and beaches by plastic materials.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750539","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-24","<p>The oral statement referred to was to bring to the notice of the House the publication of the independent Matthew Taylor Review of Modern Working Practices. Zero hours contracts are just one example of a working practice in the UK labour market and Matthew in his review has considered the labour market as a whole. I refer the noble Lord to the full transcript of the <a href="http://hansard.parliament.uk/lords/2017-07-11/debates/805C6758-D847-475F-98D2-49F75499FAF8/TaylorReviewOfModernWorkingPractices" target="_blank">statement</a> where zero hours contracts are discussed.</p><p> </p><p>This Government will give the report the careful consideration it deserves and will respond in full later this year.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-24T10:47:07.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750539/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750539/answer","Attachment to HL671.pdf","Extract from Official Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750539/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the statement by Lord Prior of Brampton on 11 July (HL Deb) on Good work: the Taylor review of modern working practices, why no reference was made to zero-hours contracts; what consideration they are giving to increasing the level of employment rights protections afforded to workers employed under such contracts towards the level afforded to full-time workers, or the self-employed; and whether they intend to introduce a right to weekly guaranteed minimum paid hours.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750540","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>The Electoral Office for Northern Ireland does not have a readily accessible record of the number of proxy votes applied for the 2015 Parliamentary election, or the Northern Ireland Assembly elections in 2016 and 2017. It would not be possible to provide the information for the number of proxy votes applied for at any election, other than the 2017 UK Parliamentary General Election, other than at disproportionate cost. The number of proxy votes granted in each of the elections requested are set out below.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T11:01:13.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750540/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750540/answer","HL672 - Table.docx","Table - UIN HL672","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750540/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how many proxy votes were (1) applied for, and (2) granted, in each Northern Ireland constituency in (a) the 2015 general election, (b) the 2017 general election, (c) the 2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election, and (d) the 2017 Northern Ireland Assembly election.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750541","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>Proxy votes must be applied for by the individual themselves; it is not possible for any other person to apply on their behalf. Under the provisions of the Representation of the People Act 1985, a person is not entitled to vote as proxy at the same parliamentary election in any constituency on behalf of more than two electors for whom that person is not the spouse or civil partner, parent, grandparent, brother, sister, child or grandchild. The Electoral Office for Northern Ireland does not keep a record of the relationships between the registered voter and their successfully appointed proxy.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T10:58:15.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750541/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750541/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how many of the proxy votes granted in Northern Ireland in the 2017 general election were applied for by (1) someone who was a close relative of the elector, and (2) a non–relative; how a close relative is defined for the purposes of the proxy vote system; and whether the Electoral Office of Northern Ireland has a computer system able to record and statistically analyse that data.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750542","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>The G markings placed against EU citizens on the electoral register denotes their eligibility to vote at local and Assembly elections. The K marking denotes an EU citizen who has confirmed that they intend to vote in Northern Ireland, rather than their home state, at a specific European Parliamentary election. The K designation only lasts for one year and consequently there are currently no individuals with a K marking on the Northern Ireland register.</p><p> </p><p>UK, Irish and Commonwealth citizens are eligible to register to vote in UK General Parliamentary Elections. Citizens of EU countries other than the UK, Ireland, Cyprus and Malta (the latter of which are Commonwealth as well as EU countries) cannot vote in UK General Parliamentary Elections, although they can register to vote at local government, and Northern Ireland Assembly elections.</p><p> </p><p>The number of EU nationals, other than Irish, Cypriot, Maltese and UK citizens, on the electoral register are shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Constituency</strong></p></td><td><p>EU nationals on the electoral register (other than Irish, Cypriot, Maltese and UK citizens)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Belfast East</strong></p></td><td><p>1943</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Belfast North</strong></p></td><td><p>1617</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Belfast South</strong></p></td><td><p>2857</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Belfast West</strong></p></td><td><p>462</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>East Antrim</strong></p></td><td><p>597</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>East Londonderry</strong></p></td><td><p>1044</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Fermanagh &amp; South Tyrone</strong></p></td><td><p>3801</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Foyle</strong></p></td><td><p>636</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Lagan Valley</strong></p></td><td><p>1330</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Mid Ulster</strong></p></td><td><p>1919</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Newry &amp; Armagh</strong></p></td><td><p>3017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>North Antrim</strong></p></td><td><p>1928</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>North Down</strong></p></td><td><p>708</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>South Antrim</strong></p></td><td><p>1233</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>South Down</strong></p></td><td><p>1165</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Strangford</strong></p></td><td><p>591</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Upper Bann</strong></p></td><td><p>4563</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Tyrone</strong></p></td><td><p>1114</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>30,525</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T11:00:05.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750542/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750542/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government How many EU nationals, other than Irish, Cypriot, Maltese and UK citizens, are on the electoral register in Northern Ireland, broken down by constituency; what is the distinction between the G and K markings placed against EU citizens on the electoral register; and what are the differences in the eligibility to vote between such EU nationals and UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750543","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>The total number of registered electors in Northern Ireland registered to vote in more than one constituency is 23.</p><p> </p><p>The Electoral Office for Northern Ireland holds data in relation to each constituency on how many people are also registered to vote in another constituency. In some constituencies this applies to fewer than five people. A full answer would risk the identification of individuals and is therefore not provided.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T10:56:20.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750543/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750543/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how many people are registered to vote in more than one constituency in Northern Ireland; and, in relation to each constituency in Northern Ireland, how many people are also registered to vote in one or more other constituency.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750544","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>Any individual wishing to appoint a proxy to vote in their place must complete an application form providing all the personal details given at registration, including their national insurance number and signature, which are checked against the register. Only those applications passing scrutiny are accepted.</p><p> </p><p>Voters are required to state the nature of their relationship to the individual they are nominating as their proxy and all forms contain the warning that making a false statement is a criminal offense. Written confirmation of successful applications is sent to both the applicant and the registered proxy at their registered addresses.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T10:58:55.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750544/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750544/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what methods are used by the Electoral Office in Northern Ireland to ascertain (1) whether someone applying for a proxy vote is a close relation of the voter, and (2) the validity of proxy vote applications.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750545","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>Individuals are entitled to vote as a proxy for an unlimited number of close relatives but may not vote as proxy at the same election in any constituency on behalf of more than two electors to whom they are not a closely related.</p><p> </p><p>The administration of proxy voting is an operational matter for the Chief Electoral Officer for Northern Ireland who will, following the Parliamentary election in June, conduct a routine post-election review of all administrative procedures. The Government will carefully consider any recommendations it receives concerning proxy voting from both the independent Electoral Commission as well as from the Chief Electoral Officer. The Government will also consider what, if any, of the changes recommended by Sir Eric Pickles in his report on tackling electoral fraud may also be appropriate for Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-07-21T10:52:05.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750545/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750545/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to require those voting by proxy to provide their national insurance number, in order to facilitate checks that proxies are not voting on behalf of more than two close relatives.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750546","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-20","<p>The European Global Navigation Satellite Systems Agency is funded from the European Union budget. It is a Union Agency established to deliver the EU’s satellite navigation programmes Galileo and EGNOS. The Agency will be responsible for operating the systems, managing the services provided and for promoting their adoption to create new industrial markets.</p><p>The Government recognises the benefits our involvement in these programmes brings for the UK.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-20T14:36:20.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750546/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750546/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the benefits and costs to the UK of membership of the European Global Navigation Satellite Systems Agency.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750547","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-25","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including the implications for the continued participation in the European Union Agency for Railways.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the exit negotiations the Government will discuss with the EU and member states how best to continue cooperation in the field of rail safety and standards.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-25T10:01:37.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750547/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750547/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the benefits and costs to the UK of membership of the European Railway Agency.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750548","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-20","<p>The European Fisheries Control Agency (EFCA) is funded from the EU budget, to which the UK is the second largest net contributor.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-07-20T15:12:26.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750548/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750548/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the benefits and costs to the UK of membership of the European Fisheries Control Agency.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750549","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-20","<p>The European Chemicals Agency (ECHA) provides a range of centralised functions across a number of EU chemicals regimes, including facilitating collective decisions amongst EU Member States. Under the EU REACH Regulation, it manages data about chemicals on the EU market. Chemicals manufactured or imported in quantities above 1 tonne a year must be registered with ECHA to access the single market.</p><p>The UK’s current involvement with ECHA comes as part of our membership of EU. ECHA is funded mainly through a combination of industry fees for a variety of the services it provides and direct EU funding. The higher the income generated from fees, the lower the EU budget subsidy. As ECHA is an agency of the EU, the UK’s contribution to its running costs is through our general contribution to the EU budget.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-07-20T15:13:15.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750549/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750549/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the benefits and costs to the UK of membership of the European Chemicals Agency.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750550","Department for Education","false","2017-07-25","<p>The European Institute of Gender Equality (EIGE) is an autonomous body of the European Union, which was established to contribute to and strengthen the promotion of gender equality. EIGE products, which include comparable data and research, have been utilised by the Government to inform evidence-based policy-making. However, there are a number of bodies, including the Council of Europe and OECD that produce similar products.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-07-25T10:08:07.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750550/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750550/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the benefits and costs to the UK of membership of the European Institute for Gender Equality.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750551","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>The European Defence Agency (EDA) has a key role in facilitating European cooperation on capability development in support of the EU's Common Security and Defence Policy. EDA membership requires a financial contribution towards the Agency's budget; this currently amounts to £3.9 million for the UK. The UK benefits from EDA work through involvement in a range of projects and initiatives, and UK industry has access to EU opportunities and funding, especially in the area of research and technology.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-07-18T15:25:52.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750551/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750551/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the benefits and costs to the UK of membership of the European Defence Agency.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750552","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>No central assessment has been made of chronic fatigue syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis (CFS/ME) clinical services established between 2004 and 2006. The commissioning of services for people with CFS/ME is a local matter, and the management of patients within such services is the responsibility of the commissioners, providers and clinicians responsible for their care. Clinical commissioning groups have a duty to exercise their functions effectively, efficiently and economically</p><p> </p><p>Since its publication in 2007, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) clinical guideline on the management of CFS/ME in adults and children, which set outs best practice on the care, treatment and support of people with the condition, has supported the local National Health Service in delivering services for people with the condition. The guidance recognises the challenges in managing a condition for which there is no definitive diagnostic test, no clear understanding of the causes and process of disease and no cure. The guidance is also clear that there is no one form of treatment to suit every patient and that treatment and care should take into account the personal needs and preferences of the patient. NICE is currently reviewing the guidance to ensure it reflects the latest available evidence and a decision regarding this matter is expected shortly.</p><p><br></p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-07-19T11:03:01.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750552/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750552/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the chronic fatigue syndrome myalgic encephalomyelitis (ME/CFS) clinical services which were set up between 2004 and 2006; what proportion of patients accessing services recover from ME/CFS or show signs of improvement; and what assessment they have made of the value for money of these services.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750553","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>There are no plans to set up an independent review of chronic fatigue syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis (CFS/ME) services. Services for patients with CFS/ME are supported by independent, evidence-based guidance produced by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence on the diagnosis, treatment and support of patients with the condition. Commissioners should deliver services that meet the needs of local popuations. Assessments of service need for CFS/ME may be supported by the available population prevalence estimates as required.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-07-19T15:08:32.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750553/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750553/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to set up an independent review of ME/CFS services which includes an epidemiological study to establish the true incidence of ME/CFS in the population and the impact of the shortage of doctors trained in this specialism; and, if not, why not.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750554","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Home Office does not centrally collect information on the number of inspections of houses or flats offering short-term accommodation to paying guests carried out by each fire and rescue authority. Information on the number of inspections of houses or flats offering short-term accommodation to paying guests is the responsibility of individual FRSs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-20T16:08:37.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750554/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750554/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 5 July (HL 50), how many inspections of houses or flats offering short–term accommodation to paying guests were carried out by each fire and rescue authority in each year since 2010; and how many of those inspections were found to be (1) satisfactory and (2) unsatisfactory.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750555","Home Office","false","2017-07-25","<p>It is the responsibility of each fire and rescue authority to manage its prevention, protection and operational resources to address effectively risks within their communities. This includes determining which premises to audit to ensure compliance with the provisions of the Fire Safety Order. When carrying out an audit, including for short-term accommodation let through Airbnb or similar platforms, it is for the individual fire and rescue authority to determine how they assess whether the fire risk assessment carried out by the responsible person and the fire precautions in place are adequate and appropriate for a particular premises. No two premises are the same. What may represent a proportionate approach to improved fire safety management in one building, will not necessarily apply in another.</p><p>The level of competency required for individual premises will vary according to their nature and complexity.</p><p>The Government issued guidance to assist enforcing authorities in their enforcement responsibilities under the Fire Safety Order, which is available here - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regulatory-reform-fire-safety-order-2005-guidance-note-enforcement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regulatory-reform-fire-safety-order-2005-guidance-note-enforcement</a>. In addition, the Chief Fire Officers Association, now the National Fire Chiefs Council, produced a standardised audit form to ensure consistency of audits.</p><p>The person responsible for complying with the Fire Safety Order (usually the owner, employer, landlord or managing agent) may decide that they are competent to carry out the risk assessment themselves or they may choose to appoint a competent person to undertake the risk assessment on their behalf. A decision on this may be made in conjunction with their insurers.</p><p>The requirements for a competent person are set out in the Fire Safety Order. A person is to be regarded as competent for the purposes of making a fire risk assessment if they have sufficient training and experience or knowledge and other qualities to enable them properly to assist in undertaking the preventative and protective measures. To help those responsible for ensuring that the risk from fire in their premises has been accurately assessed, the fire sector has produced guidance on how to choose a competent fire risk assessor. This is available on <a href="http://www.cfoa.org.uk/19532" target="_blank">www.cfoa.org.uk/19532</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, fire safety risk assessment guidance produced by the Government and by the Local Government Association also provides advice and guidance to those responsible for fire safety compliance to help them to accurately assess the risks from fire and implement adequate and appropriate fire safety measures. This is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/fire-risk-assessments" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/fire-risk-assessments</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will consider the ongoing suitability of the Fire Safety Order as part of the wider work underway following the horrific fire at Grenfell Tower.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL688 ; HL689","2017-07-25T11:23:10.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750555/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750555/answer","guidance1enforcement2005.pdf","Regulatory Reform Order Guidance ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750555/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 5 July (HL 50), what criteria fire and rescue authorities use to determine whether fire safety precautions are "adequate" and "appropriate" for the management of fire hazards in houses or flats offering accomodation to paying guests, such as through Airbnb.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750556","Home Office","false","2017-07-25","<p>It is the responsibility of each fire and rescue authority to manage its prevention, protection and operational resources to address effectively risks within their communities. This includes determining which premises to audit to ensure compliance with the provisions of the Fire Safety Order. When carrying out an audit, including for short-term accommodation let through Airbnb or similar platforms, it is for the individual fire and rescue authority to determine how they assess whether the fire risk assessment carried out by the responsible person and the fire precautions in place are adequate and appropriate for a particular premises. No two premises are the same. What may represent a proportionate approach to improved fire safety management in one building, will not necessarily apply in another.</p><p>The level of competency required for individual premises will vary according to their nature and complexity.</p><p>The Government issued guidance to assist enforcing authorities in their enforcement responsibilities under the Fire Safety Order, which is available here - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regulatory-reform-fire-safety-order-2005-guidance-note-enforcement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regulatory-reform-fire-safety-order-2005-guidance-note-enforcement</a>. In addition, the Chief Fire Officers Association, now the National Fire Chiefs Council, produced a standardised audit form to ensure consistency of audits.</p><p>The person responsible for complying with the Fire Safety Order (usually the owner, employer, landlord or managing agent) may decide that they are competent to carry out the risk assessment themselves or they may choose to appoint a competent person to undertake the risk assessment on their behalf. A decision on this may be made in conjunction with their insurers.</p><p>The requirements for a competent person are set out in the Fire Safety Order. A person is to be regarded as competent for the purposes of making a fire risk assessment if they have sufficient training and experience or knowledge and other qualities to enable them properly to assist in undertaking the preventative and protective measures. To help those responsible for ensuring that the risk from fire in their premises has been accurately assessed, the fire sector has produced guidance on how to choose a competent fire risk assessor. This is available on <a href="http://www.cfoa.org.uk/19532" target="_blank">www.cfoa.org.uk/19532</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, fire safety risk assessment guidance produced by the Government and by the Local Government Association also provides advice and guidance to those responsible for fire safety compliance to help them to accurately assess the risks from fire and implement adequate and appropriate fire safety measures. This is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/fire-risk-assessments" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/fire-risk-assessments</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will consider the ongoing suitability of the Fire Safety Order as part of the wider work underway following the horrific fire at Grenfell Tower.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL687 ; HL689","2017-07-25T11:23:11.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750556/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750556/answer","guidance1enforcement2005.pdf","Regulatory Reform Order Guidance ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750556/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 5 July (HL 50), what assessement they have made of the application and enforcement of the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 in relations to houses or flats provided as short–term accommodation to paying guests through platforms such as Airbnb; whether they have any plans to review or update the Order; and, if so, what is their planned timescale for review.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL688"
