"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750765","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) conducts statutory annual inspections and roadside enforcement checks. During statutory annual inspections, DVSA identified 2 instances of public service vehicles with tyres that had exceeded the 10-year age limit since January 2014; both instances were in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst carrying out roadside enforcement checks, DVSA has not identified any public service vehicles with tyres that have exceeded the 10-year age limit since January 2014.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-19T13:58:21.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750765/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750765/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11","Buses: Tyres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many public service vehicles inspected by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency were identified as having tyres that exceed the 10-year age limit in each year since January 2014.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","4421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750766","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The following figures show the number of public service vehicle (PSV) encounters carried out by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) in each year since January 2014 under each inspection type; tyres are inspected as part of each encounter.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Roadside</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Testing</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>13774</p></td><td><p>89732</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>6417</p></td><td><p>89057</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>9186</p></td><td><p>87488</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 (six months to June)</p></td><td><p>5737</p></td><td><p>45869</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>A memo, first issued in April 2014, to all DVSA testing and roadside examination staff requested notification to the presenter and/or driver proportionate to the condition of the vehicle, which included the age of tyres fitted to the front axle of PSVs.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-19T13:53:54.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750766/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750766/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11","Buses: Tyres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2017 to Question 1855, how many inspections into the age of public service vehicle tyres were carried out by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency in each year since January 2014.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","4420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750767","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>The information collected by the Department on the number of reported accidents involving vehicles with more than eight seated passengers from October 2012 onwards, where a tyre was considered to be a contributory factor are included in the table. In these cases, the investigating Police Officer indicated that a tyre was “illegal, defective or under inflated”.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Coach and bus (over 16 seated passengers</p></td><td><p>Minibuses (9 to 16 seated passengers)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-18T08:44:34.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750767/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750767/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11","Buses: Tyres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many accidents involving coaches or buses were caused by a defective tyre in each year since October 2012.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","4419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750768","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-19","<p>Local authorities are responsible for assessing the needs of all road users in their areas and for implementing appropriate traffic management measures. If a local authority considers that the safety of pedestrians in a particular location is compromised by pavement parking they have the powers necessary to deal with it through a Traffic Regulation Order (TRO).</p><p> </p><p>As part of our discussions with local authorities and other stakeholders, my department is planning to launch a survey in autumn 2017 in order to gather evidence about the TRO procedure, the costs and timescales for processing TROs, and information about options for change.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","4417","2017-07-19T16:24:41.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750768/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750768/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the adequacy of legislation related to parking on pavements in ensuring pedestrian safety.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","4418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750769","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-19","<p>Local authorities are responsible for assessing the needs of all road users in their areas and for implementing appropriate traffic management measures. If a local authority considers that the safety of pedestrians in a particular location is compromised by pavement parking they have the powers necessary to deal with it through a Traffic Regulation Order (TRO).</p><p> </p><p>As part of our discussions with local authorities and other stakeholders, my department is planning to launch a survey in autumn 2017 in order to gather evidence about the TRO procedure, the costs and timescales for processing TROs, and information about options for change.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","4418","2017-07-19T16:24:40.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750769/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750769/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-11","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the effect of parked cars obstructing pavements on the safety of visually impaired and blind pedestrians.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","4417"
