"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750896","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-19","<p>I have asked the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life to carry out a review of the intimidation experienced by parliamentary candidates, including those who stood to become Members of Parliament at the 2017 General Election.</p><p>This review should:</p><p>“Examine the nature of the problem and consider whether measures already in place to address such behaviour are sufficient to protect the integrity of public service; and whether such measures are (a) effective, especially given the rise of social media, and (b) enforceable</p><p>Produce a report for the Prime Minister, including recommendations for action focused on what could be done in the short- and long-term, and identifying examples of good practice.</p><p>The review will recognise the important role of legitimate scrutiny of those standing for public office by the public and the press.”</p><p>It will be for the Committee to decide its approach and to gather evidence of abuse; examine the nature of the problem; consider whether the measures already in place to address such behaviour are effective and enforceable and make recommendations for action. I look forward to receiving their findings.</p><p>I would encourage the All-Party Parliamentary Group to submit its reports and evidence to the Committee’s review.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","4220","2017-07-19T12:04:56.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750896/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750896/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-11","Candidates: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what steps she plans to take to tackle abuse of electoral candidates; what plans she has to investigate past instances of such abuse; and which Ministers will be responsible for that work.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","4219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750897","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-19","<p>I have asked the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life to carry out a review of the intimidation experienced by parliamentary candidates, including those who stood to become Members of Parliament at the 2017 General Election.</p><p>This review should:</p><p>“Examine the nature of the problem and consider whether measures already in place to address such behaviour are sufficient to protect the integrity of public service; and whether such measures are (a) effective, especially given the rise of social media, and (b) enforceable</p><p>Produce a report for the Prime Minister, including recommendations for action focused on what could be done in the short- and long-term, and identifying examples of good practice.</p><p>The review will recognise the important role of legitimate scrutiny of those standing for public office by the public and the press.”</p><p>It will be for the Committee to decide its approach and to gather evidence of abuse; examine the nature of the problem; consider whether the measures already in place to address such behaviour are effective and enforceable and make recommendations for action. I look forward to receiving their findings.</p><p>I would encourage the All-Party Parliamentary Group to submit its reports and evidence to the Committee’s review.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","4219","2017-07-19T12:04:56.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750897/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750897/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-11","Candidates: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if she will ensure that Ministers drawing up plans to tackle abuse of electoral candidates take account of the findings of the All-Party Parliamentary Group Inquiry into Electoral Conduct, published in 2013, and updates to that report.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","4220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750898","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-19","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the response given by the Prime Minister to PQ 4219 on 19<sup>th</sup> July.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-19T14:42:36.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750898/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750898/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-11","Candidates: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department plans to provide to the Minister tasked with taking forward the Government’s investigation into the abuse of electoral candidates details of the All-Party Parliamentary Group Inquiry into Electoral Conduct relating to social media and communications.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","4222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750899","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>I refer the honourable member to the answer given by the Prime Minister on the 19th July 2017 to PQ4219 and PQ4220.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-19T12:41:46.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750899/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750899/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-11","Election Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department plans to provide to the Minister tasked with taking forward the Government’s investigation into the abuse of electoral candidates details of the All-Party Parliamentary Group Inquiry into Electoral Conduct and its subsequent updates.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","4221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750900","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>NHS England is leading the development of a formal joint National Health Service arm’s length body response to the report ‘Old Problems, New Solutions’, planned for publication in autumn 2017. NHS England has been working very closely with partners and members of the Commission on Adult Acute Psychiatric Care throughout the development process.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-19T10:31:30.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750900/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750900/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the Government plans to publish a response to the report Old Problems, New Solutions: Improving Acute Psychiatric Care for Adults in England, published by the Commission on Acute Psychiatric Care in February 2016.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","4135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750902","Home Office","false","2017-08-01","<p>Following publication of our paper <em>Safeguarding the position of EU Citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU </em>on 26 June, my officials have begun discussions with a range of groups representing EU citizens in the UK, including those representing vulnerable groups.</p><p>We are committed to continuing this dialogue over the coming months. DWP publish disability facts and figures, and ONS publish statistics on the UK resident population, however these do not include data on the number of EU citizens residing in the UK who have a disability.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-08-01T09:44:10.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750902/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750902/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11","EU Nationals: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many EU citizens residing in the UK have a disability.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","4350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750903","Home Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Home Secretary and myself have meetings with a wide range of stakeholders, and senior Home Office officials have begun discussions with a range of groups representing EU citizens in the UK, including those representing vulnerable groups. We are committed to continuing and broadening this dialogue over the coming months.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-19T15:48:52.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750903/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750903/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750903/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with disability groups on the effect of proposals for settled status on EU citizens in the caring professions living in the UK.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","4335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750904","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government has led the way on the transparency of beneficial ownership information. The UK was the first G20 country to establish a public register of company beneficial ownership. Earlier this month, HM Revenue and Customs launched a beneficial ownership register for trusts with tax consequences.</p><p> </p><p>Trusts and companies are fundamentally different, so these registers have different levels of access. Unlike companies, trusts are typically used for private reasons like managing assets for minors and vulnerable persons. Law enforcement should be able to identify who owns and benefits from trusts, but publishing these persons’ details would not be proportionate.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-17T15:07:30.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750904/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750904/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-11","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward proposals to require the beneficial ownership of companies and trusts to be made public.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","4351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750905","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-17","<p>In their March forecast, the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) expected inflation to average 2.4% in 2017 before falling back to 2.3% in 2018 and 2.0% from 2019 to 2021.</p><p> </p><p>Maintaining price stability is the primary objective of the Monetary Policy Committee. This objective is defined as an inflation target of 2% as measured by the twelve month increase in the Consumer Prices Index.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is taking action to support people with the cost of living. This includes increasing the National Living Wage, raising the personal allowance, and freezing fuel duty.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-17T10:51:19.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750905/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750905/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-11","Inflation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to tackle rising inflation.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","4349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750906","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-17","<p>According to the Office for National Statistics (ONS), total pay increased by 1.8% on the year in the three months to May. The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) also expect wages to increase in each year of their forecast.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is taking action to support wages. Introduced in April 2016, the National Living Wage has benefitted around 1.7 million low paid workers and delivered the fastest wage growth for the lowest paid in 20 years. Furthermore, the Government has boosted take home pay with increases to personal allowance, where 1.3 million individuals will be taken out of income tax this year.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-17T10:59:21.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750906/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750906/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-11","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to tackle wage stagnation.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","4352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750907","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The government is currently considering over 140,000 responses to the consultation on the Leveson Inquiry and its implementation.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-17T14:01:30.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750907/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750907/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-11","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish her response to the Leveson Inquiry and its implementation.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","4204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750908","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Foreign Secretary met His Excellency Adel al Jubeir, the Saudi Arabian Foreign Minister, on Friday 7 July to discuss a full range of regional and bilateral issues, including the current tensions in the Gulf.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-17T16:41:10.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750908/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750908/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Saudi Arabia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he last met his counterpart in Saudi Arabia; and what issues were discussed at that meeting.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","4178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750909","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Increasingly, our customers access many of our services on-line. This includes claiming benefits, looking for jobs and keeping us informed of their efforts to find work.</p><p>The roll out of Universal Credit and our reforms of Jobcentre Plus have increased the number of interactions claimants now have with us online. For example, eight out of ten claims for Jobseeker’s Allowance are now made online and 99.6% of applicants for Universal Credit full service submitted their claim online, reflecting increased digital capability and accessibility. This allows the Department to tailor its service so that face-to-face contact can be focused on those who need extra support.</p><p><br>We are committed to retaining an accessible jobcentre network and continuing to serve customers in all areas and the face to face support our work coaches offer at jobcentres will continue to be a core part of the service we deliver. In order to be able to support customers in the most appropriate way, we have various means of interacting with them, including face to face, e-mail, telephone and by post.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T10:57:55.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750909/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750909/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-11","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment  he has made of the potential effect of jobcentre closures on claimants who have difficulty using PCs and the Internet.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","4177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750910","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Changes to the DWP estate announced on 5 July are not intended to reduce the number of staff or level of service we deliver, they are about redesigning our estate in a way that provides value for the taxpayer while continuing to support to our claimants.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst no specific estimate has been made of the additional caseload for Cofa Court Jobcentre as a result of these changes, the number of work coaches in jobcentres is set to increase in all areas which will offset any increases.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T10:58:28.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750910/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750910/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-11","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate  he has made of the additional caseload for Cofa Court Jobcentre in Coventry as a result of closure of the Torrington Avenue Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","4179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750911","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-17","<p>In the 12 months to 1st June 2017, the UK reported a trade surpluses of £175m in milk and cream, £30m in Cheddar cheese and £471m in Gin, and a trade deficit of £168m in fresh strawberries (Source: HMRC Overseas Trade Statistics <a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/BuildYourOwnTables/Pages/Home.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/BuildYourOwnTables/Pages/Home.aspx</a>).</p><p>The Harmonised Commodity Description and Coding System (HS) nomenclature, an internationally standardised system used to classify traded products, does not provide a unique code for cream. Rather, milk and cream are grouped together.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-17T16:24:04.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750911/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750911/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-11","Balance of Trade: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, What the overall trade surplus was in (a) strawberries, (b) cream, (c) cheddar cheese and (d) gin in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","4180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750912","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>No central record is held of global expenditure on wines and spirits in the UK and overseas by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO).</p><p>The Government Wine Cellar is managed by the FCO's Protocol Departmentand has been self-financing since 2011. All costs covered by sales of older, higher value stock. Since 2012 the FCO has spent the following amounts on new stocks of wines and spirits:</p><p>2011/12 - £48 955</p><p>2012/13 - £45 866</p><p>2013/14 - £50 054</p><p>2014/15 - £70 432</p><p>2015/16 - £40 177.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-17T16:36:18.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750912/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750912/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on new stocks of wines and spirits for hospitality purposes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750913","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>This information is publicly available on the Gov.uk website. The FCO accounts for hospitality expenditure under Business Hospitality and representations of the FCO.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-17T16:41:40.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750913/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750913/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has spent on hospitality in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750914","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>I have not raised the issue of financial contributions to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe with my Russian counterpart. The amount each participating State pays to the organisation is calculated based on a scale of assessment. Efforts to amend that scale are ongoing. The UK argues strongly in these discussions that a new scale should be based on the capacity to pay, applying the UN methodology based on Gross National Income (GNI). Adoption of this new scale would result in increased contributions from a number of countries including Russia.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-19T13:32:26.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750914/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750914/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Russia: Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Russian counterpart on that country increasing its funding contribution to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750915","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>I have not held bilateral discussions with Armenian or Azerbaijani counterparts about their financial contributions to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe. The amount each participating State pays to the Organisation is calculated on a scale of assessment. Efforts to amend that scale are ongoing. The UK argues strongly in these discussions that a new scale should be based on the capacity to pay, applying the UN methodology based on Gross National Income (GNI). Adoption of this new scale would result in increased contributions from a number of countries including Armenia and Azerbaijan.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-18T16:26:09.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750915/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750915/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Armenia and Azerbaijan: Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) Armenia and (b) Azerbaijan on those states increasing their funding contributions to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750916","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>The United Kingdom's assessed contributions to the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe's Unified (regular) Budget IS 9.35% of the total budget. It is paid in Euros and in the last ten years were approximately as in the table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Cost</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>€16.4m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>€14.5m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>€14.4m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>€14.9m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>€14.7m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>€14.7m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>€15.2m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>€14.3m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>€14.3m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>€14.6m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The United Kingdom's contributions to the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe's Special Monitoring Mission to Ukraine AT 11.9%, which is funded separately from the Unified Budget as specified in its mandate, since it's commencement in 2014 were approximately as in the table:</p><p> </p><p>Year Costs</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>€3,513,923m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>€7,208,500m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>€8,328,589m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>(Estimated) €8,084,743m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the United Kingdom has provided voluntary contributions towards the deployment of election observers to various ODIHR missions across the OSCE in the last ten years approximately as in the table:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Cost</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>£144,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>£200,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£660,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£279,903</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£304,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£398,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£619,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£583,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>£571,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>£104,000 (to end June 2017</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK has also contributed bilateral funding to various OSCE implemented projects over the past ten years. Funding for these projects were agreed on a case by case basis and there is no central record of all the contributions held.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-19T13:30:19.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750916/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750916/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much funding the Government has provided to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750917","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>We have not made representations to the US Government on the level of their assistance to Tunisia. UK support to Tunisia has risen to £10 million for this year.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-19T12:27:04.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750917/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750917/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750917/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-11","Tunisia: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his US counterpart on the US State Department’s planned financial reductions to bilateral assistance for Tunisia.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750918","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence art collection has been disestablished and ownership of the most significant antiques and paintings transferred to other public institutions in order to ensure their continued protection and public display. The written ministerial statement of 12 May 2016 (Reference HLWS698) states the art collection was to be transferred on an unvalued basis. In accordance with the Department for Culture Media and Sport policy the collection as a whole was not valued, meaning the items were gifted to the public institutions. No items from the collection have been sold as it is against normal practice to sell any artwork.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-17T14:01:55.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750918/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750918/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Ministry of Defence: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what stocks of (a) antiques, (b) paintings and (c) fine wines are held by his Department; if he will list any such assets sold over the last five years together with the sale proceeds from such transactions; and whether he plans to sell further such assets.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750919","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Government Hospitality Fund is run by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office for the benefit of Ministers across Government.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-17T14:00:45.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750919/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750919/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Ministry of Defence: Government Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the value was of repayments his Department made to Government Hospitality for wines and spirits in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750920","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Department meets routinely with representatives of BAE Systems to discuss a range of matters including the TF-X programme. The Department has also held meetings with the Turkish government which have been attended by representatives of Turkish Aerospace Industries when it was appropriate for them to do so.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-18T14:47:51.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750920/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750920/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Turkey: Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent meetings his Department has had with representatives from (a) BAE Systems and (b) Turkish Aerospace Industries on the development of the proposed TFX fighter aircraft.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750921","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The mechanisms that cover the de-confliction of Syrian airspace remain in place. The UK takes all steps necessary to ensure the safety of its aircraft operating in Syrian airspace, which includes reacting to the changing threat profiles.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-17T14:12:35.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750921/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750921/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 27 October 2016 to Question 49899, what assessment he has made of the implications of his Department’s policies of the announcement by the Russian defence ministry that it is halting cooperation with the US within the framework of the Memorandum on the Prevention of Incidents and Ensuring Air Safety in Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750922","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>We welcome - and will support - any initiative which will bring about a peaceful resolution to the civil war in Syria. The ceasefire will not have any implications for the UK's policies for Syria which are focussed on the fight against Daesh.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-17T13:59:35.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750922/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750922/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department’s policies of the US and Russian Federation’s ceasefire deal in South-West Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750923","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>The priorities for integration into the carriers at the initial operating capability in 2020 remain F-35B Lightning, Maritime Force Protection Helicopters (Merlin Mk2 ASW/Crowsnest) and Battlefield Helicopters. With a planned life of around 50 years, we will continue to review the capabilities to be integrated into the Queen Elizabeth Class carriers in line with other Defence investment priorities at the appropriate time.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","4337","2017-07-18T13:37:53.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750923/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750923/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Aircraft Carriers: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what funding has been (a) approved and (b) considered for the development of an additional unmanned air systems capability for the Queen Elizabeth class aircraft carriers.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750924","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>The priorities for integration into the carriers at the initial operating capability in 2020 remain F-35B Lightning, Maritime Force Protection Helicopters (Merlin Mk2 ASW/Crowsnest) and Battlefield Helicopters. With a planned life of around 50 years, we will continue to review the capabilities to be integrated into the Queen Elizabeth Class carriers in line with other Defence investment priorities at the appropriate time.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","4336","2017-07-18T13:37:53.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750924/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750924/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Aircraft Carriers: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which unmanned air systems (UAS) are planned to operate from the Queen Elizabeth class carriers from initial operational capability; and whether he intends to conduct a review of UAS that could be marinised and deployed on those carriers.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750925","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>The exact nature of our future EU relationship will be determined as part of the Brexit negotiations.</p><p>We are seeking a deep and special partnership with our European partners after we leave the EU, which will encompass both economic and security cooperation. We have the largest European defence budget and we want to continue contributing to the security of Europe, building and enhancing our wider cooperation and using our range of defence and security capabilities, our global standing, and our networks and influence.</p><p>The UK will continue to have all of the rights and obligations that membership brings, including receiving European funding, up until the point we leave the EU. We recognise that many organisations across the UK which are in receipt of EU funding, or expect to start receiving funding, want reassurance about the flow of funding they will receive. In line with wider commitments to Horizon research funding, funding received from the EU's defence research programme prior to our exit from the EU will be guaranteed after we leave.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-18T13:33:40.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750925/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750925/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-11","Defence: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure UK manufacturers will be able to continue to engage with EU defence research and development programmes after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","4233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750926","Department of Health","false","2017-07-17","<p>Lactose (milk sugar) is commonly used as a diluent in solid oral dosage forms such as tablets and capsules; however is rarely present in oral liquid presentations or parenteral dosage forms, such as injections. While no list of “lactose-free” medicines is maintained, the presence or absence of lactose in any licensed medicine, including those for breast cancer, can be readily identified.</p><p> </p><p>Where a medicine contains lactose, this is highlighted, together with the quantity of lactose, within the Summary of Product Characteristics. The package leaflet for that medicine will also highlight in qualitative terms whether the medicine contains lactose. The package leaflet is provided with each pack of medicine sold or dispensed in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>The British National Formulary, a standard medical text in the UK, advises that the lactose content in most medicines is too small to cause problems in most lactose-intolerant patients. However, in patients with severe lactose intolerance, lactose content should be determined before prescribing especially if they are taking several products containing lactose.</p><p> </p><p>Clinicians prescribe the medicines and drugs that are most appropriate for their patient, taking into account all relevant factors and guidance. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency, which is responsible for the regulation of medicines in the UK, will help prescribers to establish the availability of a lactose free version of any particular medicine.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-17T15:49:05.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750926/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750926/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of drugs for the treatment and post-treatment needs of breast cancer patients contain lactose; and what provision is made for breast cancer patients who are intolerant or allergic to lactose.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","4161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750927","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>This information is not collated or retained centrally in the Home Office.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-17T16:02:15.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750927/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750927/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11","Home Office: Mass Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many public engagements for which a media calling notice was issued were attended by a departmental Minister in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750928","Home Office","false","2018-01-11","<p>The Home Office constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government’s agenda. The Department responded quickly to the challenges following the EU referendum last June. With negotiations now underway, we continue to assess how our priorities will impact on the workforce and capabilities required.</p><p>Operational units across the Home Office actively monitor workflows to ensure sufficient resources are in place to meet demand and will continue to do so throughout negotiations and as the UK leaves the EU. Any resultant changes to resource requirements will be factored into strategic planning.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-01-11T17:31:47.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750928/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750928/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-11","UK Border Force: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Border Force officers are currently employed; and how many such officers she estimates will be required after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750929","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-19T10:51:29.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750929/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750929/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-11","Department of Health: Mass Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many public engagements for which a media calling notice was issued were attended by a departmental Minister in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750930","Scotland Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>The number of public engagements for which a media calling notice was issued which was attended by a departmental Minister in each of the last 12 months is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>June 2016</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2016</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2016</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2016</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2017</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2017</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2017</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2017</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2017</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2017</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2017</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-07-19T16:55:09.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750930/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750930/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-11","Scotland Office: Mass Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many public engagements for which a media calling notice was issued were attended by a departmental Minister in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4304"
